{"title_page": "Maureen Brady", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer and editor}}\n'''Maureen Brady''' (born 1943) is an American writer, editor and educator. She is best known for her novels<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ferguson|first=Mary Anne|date=1980|title=Images of Women in Literature: An Evolution|journal=The Radical Teacher|issue=17|pages=34\u201336|issn=0191-4847|jstor=20709278}}</ref> ''Ginger's Fire'', ''Folly'',<ref name=\"blog.pshares.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.pshares.org/index.php/the-labor-movement-and-maureen-bradys-folly/|title=The Labor Movement and Maureen Brady's Folly|website=blog.pshares.org|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> and ''Give Me Your Good Ear''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministpress.org/authors/maureen-brady|title=Maureen Brady|website=Feminist Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=stevens|first=wendy|date=1979|editor-last=Brady|editor-first=Maureen|title=give me your good ear|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=9|issue=4|pages=22|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25773043}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Short|first=Kayann|date=1996|editor-last=Arnold|editor-first=June|editor2-last=Nachman/Dykewomon|editor2-first=Elana|editor3-last=Harris|editor3-first=Bertha|editor4-last=Brady|editor4-first=Maureen|title=Do-It-Yourself Feminism|journal=The Women's Review of Books|volume=13|issue=4|pages=20\u201321|doi=10.2307/4022268|issn=0738-1433|jstor=4022268}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=dejanikus|first=tacie|date=1980|title=our legacy|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=10|issue=10|pages=17\u201325|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25773355}}</ref> She currently lives and works in [[New York City]] and [[Woodstock, New York|Woodstock, NY]].\n\n== Biography ==\nMaureen Brady was born in 1943 in [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]], [[New York (state)|New York]] and spent her adolescence in Florida. She practised as a physical therapist and also taught [[physical therapy]] at [[Russell Sage College]], [[Troy, New York]].<ref name=\"Glens1\"/> In 1977, she attended a New School workshop in writing which gave her the confidence to begin writing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sorrel|first=Lorraine|last2=Sojourner|first2=Susan|last3=Brady|first3=Maureen|date=1983|title=interview: Maureen Brady: envisioning possibilities|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=13|issue=4|pages=14\u201316|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25774961}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, she wrote the novel ''Folly'' out of a desire to cast a woman who was an outsider in her community splintered by racism, homophobia, patriarchy and capitalism as a hero.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pt6pDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|title=Folly|last=Brady|first=Maureen|date=2016-08-15|publisher=The Feminist Press at CUNY|isbn=9781558614154|language=en}}</ref> The novel focuses on a [[workers strike]] of [[North Carolina]] [[garment worker]]s with various sub-plots about the diverse set of characters lives in a [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregated]] town.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=Julia|date=1998|title=Tangled Threads: Two Novels About Women in the Textile Trades, \"Call the Darkness Light\" by Nancy Zaroulis and Folly by Maureen Brady|journal=Women's Studies Quarterly|volume=26|issue=1/2|pages=98\u2013112|issn=0732-1562|jstor=40003463}}</ref> The novel has been described as \"pro-labor, feminist, anti-racist, queer positive.\"<ref name=\"blog.pshares.org\"/> In 1994, it was reprinted as a [[classic]] by [[The Feminist Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministpress.org/books-a-m/folly|title=Folly|website=Feminist Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>\n\nBrady has received awards and fellowships from the Ludwig Vogelstein Foundation, the New York State Creative Arts Public Service program<ref name=\"Glens1\">{{cite news |title=Writer awarded grant |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/348417160/?terms=%22Maureen%2BBrady%22 |accessdate=12 April 2019 |work=The Post-Star |date=3 April 1979 |location=Glens Falls, New York |page=8}}</ref> of the [[New York State Council on the Arts]], the Briarcombe Foundation, and the [[Virginia Center for the Creative Arts]].\n\nIn 1978, Brady founded the lesbian feminist publishing company [[Spinsters Ink]] with Judith McDaniel.<ref name=\"DeBold\">{{cite journal |last1=DeBold |first1=Kathleen |title=Bellas Lettres |journal=Lambda Book Report |date=September 2000 |volume=9 |issue=2 |page=13 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=3565353&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=1048-9487}}</ref> As one of the oldest lesbian feminist publishers in the world, Spinsters Ink is widely regarded as a pioneering feminist institution.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmhFCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA460|title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary LGBTQ Literature of the United States [2 volumes]|last=Nelson|first=Emmanuel S.|date=2009-07-14|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313348600|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LFgACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA331|title=Out of the Closet, Into the Archives: Researching Sexual Histories|last=Stone|first=Amy L.|last2=Cantrell|first2=Jaime|date=2015-11-20|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=9781438459035|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://outhistory.org/exhibits/show/lesbians-20th-century/lesbian-feminism|title=Lesbian Feminism, 1960s and 1970s \u00b7 Lesbians in the Twentieth Century, 1900-1999 \u00b7 outhistory.org|website=outhistory.org|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=wilson|first=barbara|date=1984|title=European Feminist Publishing|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=14|issue=5|pages=14\u201315|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25775107}}</ref> Brady has served as the editor of many books, including ''[[The Cancer Journals]]'' by [[Audre Lorde]], Spinsters Ink (1980), and ''The Words of a Woman Who Breathes Fire: Poetry and Prose'' by Kitty Tsui, Spinsters Ink (1983).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cl-4yFFql8gC&pg=PA198|title=City of Friends: A Portrait of the Gay and Lesbian Community in America|last=LeVay|first=Simon|last2=Nonas|first2=Elisabeth|date=1997|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=9780262621137|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA page from one of Brady's manuscripts was included in \"Statements from Lesbian Artists\", which accompanied the 1978 exhibition ''A Lesbian Show.''<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=Robbins|first=Jill|chapter=Toward Lesbian Visibility|date=2011-06-21|pages=117\u2013124|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|isbn=9780816669899|doi=10.5749/minnesota/9780816669899.003.0007|title=Crossing through Chueca}}</ref>  Curated by [[Harmony Hammond]], the show was the first lesbian-identified art exhibition in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitecolumns.org/archive/index.php/Detail/Object/Show/object_id/54|title=White Columns Archive|website=www.whitecolumns.org|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBrady has taught writing at [[Skidmore College]], [[Bard College]], and The Resource Center for Accessible Living in [[Kingston, New York|Kingston, NY]]. She currently teaches creative writing at [[New York University]], the [http://www.newyorkwritersworkshop.com/about-us/about-us New York Writers Workshop] and the [https://www.peripateticwritingandart.org/home Peripatetic Writing Workshop].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sps.nyu.edu/professional-pathways/faculty/1028-maureen-brady.html|title=Faculty Profile: Maureen Brady, Adjunct Assistant Professor {{!}} NYU SPS Professional Pathways|website=www.sps.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorkwritersworkshop.com/faculty-2|title=Faculty|website=New York Writers Workshop|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref>\n\nBrady serves as the board president of the [[Barbara Deming Memorial Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://demingfund.org/our-board-amp-staff-pd-7.php|title=Barbara Deming Memorial Fund, Inc. : Our Board & Staff|website=demingfund.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Give Me Your Good Ear'', Spinsters Ink (1979)\n* ''Folly'', Feminist Press at the City University of New York (1982)<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Rebecca |title=Folly (Book) |journal=Library Journal |date=15 January 1983 |volume=108 |issue=2 |page=144 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lxh&AN=7671375&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=0363-0277}}</ref><ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite journal |last1=Rogers |first1=Michael |title=Book reviews: Classic returns |journal=Library Journal |date=August 1994 |volume=119 |issue=13 |page=141 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=9409017843&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=0363-0277}}</ref>\n* ''The Question She Put to Herself'', Crossing Press (1987)\n* ''Daybreak: Meditations for Women Survivors of Sexual Abuse'', Hazelden Publishing (1991)<ref name=\"Adolescence\">{{cite journal |title=Book reviews: BRADY, Maureen. DAYBREAK: Meditations for Women Survivors of Sexual Abuse |journal=Adolescence |date=Winter 1993 |volume=28 |issue=112 |page=991 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=9402100683&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=0001-8449}}</ref>\n*''Beyond Survival: A Writing Journey for Healing Childhood Sexual Abuse,'' HarperCollins (1992)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1988|title=Dykes to Watch Out For: ONE AFTERNOON IN THE GROVES OF ACADEME|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=18|issue=6|pages=22|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25796412}}</ref>\n* ''Midlife: Meditations for Wome''n, HarperCollins (1995)\n* ''Ginger's Fire'', Alice Street Editions/Harrington Park Press (2005)<ref name=\"Eklund\">{{cite journal |last1=Eklund |first1=Jane |title=From the Ashes |journal=Lambda Book Report |date=February 2004 |volume=12 |issue=7 |pages=18\u201319 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=13798027&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=1048-9487}}</ref>\n* ''Getaway'', Bacon Press Books (2018)\n\n== Anthologies ==\n\n*''Lesbian Texts and Contexts: Radical Revisions,'' NYU Press (1990)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ge48DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=%22Maureen+Brady%22#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20Brady%22&f=false|title=Lesbian Texts and Contexts: Radical Revisions|last=Jay|first=Karla|last2=Glasgow|first2=Joanne|last3=Vivien|first3=Renee|last4=Young|first4=Allen|date=1990|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9780814741771|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Lovers: Stories by Women,'' Crossing Press (1992)\n* ''Catholic Girls'', Plume (1992)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/sumrall-amber-coverdale-patrice-vecchione-eds/catholic-girls-3/|title=CATHOLIC GIRLS by Sumrall Amber Coverdale & Patrice Vecchione--Eds. {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Contemporary Lesbian Writers of the United States: A Bio-Bibliographical Sourcebook'', Greenwood Press (1993)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bepl.ent.sirsi.net/client/en_US/default/search/detailnonmodal/ent:$002f$002fSD_ILS$002f0$002fSD_ILS:804838/ada|title=Contemporary lesbian writers of the United States : a bio-bibliographical critical sourcebook|website=bepl.ent.sirsi.net|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=List of biographical dictionaries of women writers in English|date=2019-03-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_biographical_dictionaries_of_women_writers_in_English&oldid=889343862|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n*''A Loving Testimony: Remembering Loved Ones Lost to AIDS,'' Crossing Press (1995)\n*''Cabbage and Bones: An Anthology of Irish-American Women's Fiction'', Holt Paperbacks (1997)\n*''Touching Fire: Erotic Writings by Women'', Running Press (1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-88184-527-3|title=Touching Fire: Erotic Writings by Women |website=www.publishersweekly.com|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n*''Queer View Mirror 2: Lesbian and Gay Short Fiction'', Arsenal Pulp Press (2002)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quillandquire.com/review/queer-view-mirror-2-lesbian-and-gay-short-short-fiction/|title=Queer View Mirror 2: Lesbian and Gay Short Short Fiction|date=2007-10-11|website=Quill and Quire|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n*''Queer View Mirror: Lesbian and Gay Short Fiction,'' Arsenal Pulp Press (2002)\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.maureenbradyny.com/ Official website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brady, Maureen}}\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Feminist writers]]\n[[Category:Queer feminists]]\n[[Category:LGBT feminists]]\n[[Category:Lesbian culture in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lesbian culture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Editors]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related media in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lesbian feminist literature]]\n[[Category:Lesbian feminist media]]\n[[Category:Lesbian literature]]\n[[Category:Working-class feminism]]\n[[Category:Working-class writers]]\n[[Category:Lesbian working-class culture]]\n[[Category:Lesbian academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer and editor}}\n'''Maureen Brady''' (born 1943) is an American writer, editor and educator. She is best known for her novels<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ferguson|first=Mary Anne|date=1980|title=Images of Women in Literature: An Evolution|journal=The Radical Teacher|issue=17|pages=34\u201336|issn=0191-4847|jstor=20709278}}</ref> ''Ginger's Fire'', ''Folly'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.pshares.org/index.php/the-labor-movement-and-maureen-bradys-folly/|title=The Labor Movement and Maureen Brady's Folly|website=blog.pshares.org|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> and ''Give Me Your Good Ear''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministpress.org/authors/maureen-brady|title=Maureen Brady|website=Feminist Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=stevens|first=wendy|date=1979|editor-last=Brady|editor-first=Maureen|title=give me your good ear|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=9|issue=4|pages=22|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25773043}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Short|first=Kayann|date=1996|editor-last=Arnold|editor-first=June|editor2-last=Nachman/Dykewomon|editor2-first=Elana|editor3-last=Harris|editor3-first=Bertha|editor4-last=Brady|editor4-first=Maureen|title=Do-It-Yourself Feminism|journal=The Women's Review of Books|volume=13|issue=4|pages=20\u201321|doi=10.2307/4022268|issn=0738-1433|jstor=4022268}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=dejanikus|first=tacie|date=1980|title=our legacy|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=10|issue=10|pages=17\u201325|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25773355}}</ref> She currently lives and works in [[New York City]] and [[Woodstock, New York|Woodstock, NY]].   \n\n== Biography ==\nMaureen Brady was born in 1943 in [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]], [[New York (state)|New York]] and spent her adolescence in Florida. She practised as a physical therapist and also taught [[physical therapy]] at [[Russell Sage College]], [[Troy, New York]].<ref name=\"Glens1\"/> In 1977, she attended a New School workshop in writing which gave her the confidence to begin writing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Sorrel|first=Lorraine|last2=Sojourner|first2=Susan|last3=Brady|first3=Maureen|date=1983|title=interview: Maureen Brady: envisioning possibilities|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=13|issue=4|pages=14\u201316|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25774961}}</ref> \n\nIn 1982, she wrote the novel ''Folly'' out of a desire to cast a woman who was an outsider in her community splintered by racism, homophobia, patriarchy and capitalism as a hero.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pt6pDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|title=Folly|last=Brady|first=Maureen|date=2016-08-15|publisher=The Feminist Press at CUNY|isbn=9781558614154|language=en}}</ref> The novel focuses on a [[workers strike]] of [[North Carolina]] [[Garment worker|garment workers]] with various sub-plots about the diverse set of characters lives in a [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregated]] town.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stein|first=Julia|date=1998|title=Tangled Threads: Two Novels About Women in the Textile Trades, \"Call the Darkness Light\" by Nancy Zaroulis and Folly by Maureen Brady|journal=Women's Studies Quarterly|volume=26|issue=1/2|pages=98\u2013112|issn=0732-1562|jstor=40003463}}</ref> The novel has been described as \"pro-labor, feminist, anti-racist, queer positive.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.pshares.org/index.php/the-labor-movement-and-maureen-bradys-folly/|title=The Labor Movement and Maureen Brady's Folly|website=blog.pshares.org|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref> In 1994, it was reprinted as a [[classic]] by [[The Feminist Press]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feministpress.org/books-a-m/folly|title=Folly|website=Feminist Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>  \n\nBrady has received awards and fellowships from the Ludwig Vogelstein Foundation, the New York State Creative Arts Public Service program<ref name=\"Glens1\">{{cite news |title=Writer awarded grant |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/348417160/?terms=%22Maureen%2BBrady%22 |accessdate=12 April 2019 |work=The Post-Star |date=3 April 1979 |location=Glens Falls, New York |page=8}}</ref> of the [[New York State Council on the Arts]], the Briarcombe Foundation, and the [[Virginia Center for the Creative Arts|Virginia Center for the Creative Arts.]] \n\nIn 1978, Brady founded the lesbian feminist publishing company [[Spinsters Ink]] with Judith McDaniel.<ref name=\"DeBold\">{{cite journal |last1=DeBold |first1=Kathleen |title=Bellas Lettres |journal=Lambda Book Report |date=September 2000 |volume=9 |issue=2 |page=13 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=3565353&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=1048-9487}}</ref> As one of the oldest lesbian feminist publishers in the world, Spinsters Ink is widely regarded as a pioneering feminist institution.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmhFCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA460|title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary LGBTQ Literature of the United States [2 volumes]|last=Nelson|first=Emmanuel S.|date=2009-07-14|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313348600|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LFgACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA331|title=Out of the Closet, Into the Archives: Researching Sexual Histories|last=Stone|first=Amy L.|last2=Cantrell|first2=Jaime|date=2015-11-20|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=9781438459035|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://outhistory.org/exhibits/show/lesbians-20th-century/lesbian-feminism|title=Lesbian Feminism, 1960s and 1970s \u00b7 Lesbians in the Twentieth Century, 1900-1999 \u00b7 outhistory.org|website=outhistory.org|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=wilson|first=barbara|date=1984|title=European Feminist Publishing|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=14|issue=5|pages=14\u201315|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25775107}}</ref> Brady has served as the editor of many books, including ''[[The Cancer Journals]]'' by [[Audre Lorde]], Spinsters Ink (1980), and ''The Words of a Woman Who Breathes Fire: Poetry and Prose'' by Kitty Tsui, Spinsters Ink (1983).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cl-4yFFql8gC&pg=PA198|title=City of Friends: A Portrait of the Gay and Lesbian Community in America|last=LeVay|first=Simon|last2=Nonas|first2=Elisabeth|date=1997|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=9780262621137|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> \n\nA page from one of Brady's manuscripts was included in \"Statements from Lesbian Artists\", which accompanied the 1978 exhibition ''A Lesbian Show.''<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|last=Robbins|first=Jill|chapter=Toward Lesbian Visibility|date=2011-06-21|pages=117\u2013124|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|isbn=9780816669899|doi=10.5749/minnesota/9780816669899.003.0007|title=Crossing through Chueca}}</ref>  Curated by [[Harmony Hammond]], the show was the first lesbian-identified art exhibition in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitecolumns.org/archive/index.php/Detail/Object/Show/object_id/54|title=White Columns Archive|website=www.whitecolumns.org|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nBrady has taught writing at [[Skidmore College]], [[Bard College]], and The Resource Center for Accessible Living in [[Kingston, New York|Kingston, NY]]. She currently teaches creative writing at [[New York University]], the [http://www.newyorkwritersworkshop.com/about-us/about-us New York Writers Workshop] and the [https://www.peripateticwritingandart.org/home Peripatetic Writing Workshop].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sps.nyu.edu/professional-pathways/faculty/1028-maureen-brady.html|title=Faculty Profile: Maureen Brady, Adjunct Assistant Professor {{!}} NYU SPS Professional Pathways|website=www.sps.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorkwritersworkshop.com/faculty-2|title=Faculty|website=New York Writers Workshop|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref> \n\nBrady serves as the board president of the [[Barbara Deming Memorial Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://demingfund.org/our-board-amp-staff-pd-7.php|title=Barbara Deming Memorial Fund, Inc. : Our Board & Staff|website=demingfund.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>  \n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Give Me Your Good Ear'', Spinsters Ink (1979)\n* ''Folly'', Feminist Press at the City University of New York (1982)<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite journal |last1=Taylor |first1=Rebecca |title=Folly (Book) |journal=Library Journal |date=15 January 1983 |volume=108 |issue=2 |page=144 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=lxh&AN=7671375&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=0363-0277}}</ref><ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite journal |last1=Rogers |first1=Michael |title=Book reviews: Classic returns |journal=Library Journal |date=August 1994 |volume=119 |issue=13 |page=141 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=9409017843&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=0363-0277}}</ref>\n* ''The Question She Put to Herself'', Crossing Press (1987)\n* ''Daybreak: Meditations for Women Survivors of Sexual Abuse'', Hazelden Publishing (1991)<ref name=\"Adolescence\">{{cite journal |title=Book reviews: BRADY, Maureen. DAYBREAK: Meditations for Women Survivors of Sexual Abuse |journal=Adolescence |date=Winter 1993 |volume=28 |issue=112 |page=991 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=9402100683&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=0001-8449}}</ref>\n*''Beyond Survival: A Writing Journey for Healing Childhood Sexual Abuse,'' HarperCollins (1992)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1988|title=Dykes to Watch Out For: ONE AFTERNOON IN THE GROVES OF ACADEME|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=18|issue=6|pages=22|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25796412}}</ref>\n* ''Midlife: Meditations for Wome''n, HarperCollins (1995)\n* ''Ginger's Fire'', Alice Street Editions/Harrington Park Press (2005)<ref name=\"Eklund\">{{cite journal |last1=Eklund |first1=Jane |title=From the Ashes |journal=Lambda Book Report |date=February 2004 |volume=12 |issue=7 |pages=18\u201319 |url=http://search.ebscohost.com.rp.nla.gov.au/login.aspx?direct=true&db=f5h&AN=13798027&site=ehost-live |accessdate=12 April 2019 |issn=1048-9487}}</ref>\n* ''Getaway'', Bacon Press Books (2018)\n\n== Anthologies ==\n\n*''Lesbian Texts and Contexts: Radical Revisions,'' NYU Press (1990)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ge48DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&dq=%22Maureen+Brady%22#v=onepage&q=%22Maureen%20Brady%22&f=false|title=Lesbian Texts and Contexts: Radical Revisions|last=Jay|first=Karla|last2=Glasgow|first2=Joanne|last3=Vivien|first3=Renee|last4=Young|first4=Allen|date=1990|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9780814741771|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Lovers: Stories by Women,'' Crossing Press (1992)\n* ''Catholic Girls'', Plume (1992)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/sumrall-amber-coverdale-patrice-vecchione-eds/catholic-girls-3/|title=CATHOLIC GIRLS by Sumrall Amber Coverdale & Patrice Vecchione--Eds. {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en}}</ref>\n*''Contemporary Lesbian Writers of the United States: A Bio-Bibliographical Sourcebook'', Greenwood Press (1993)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bepl.ent.sirsi.net/client/en_US/default/search/detailnonmodal/ent:$002f$002fSD_ILS$002f0$002fSD_ILS:804838/ada|title=Contemporary lesbian writers of the United States : a bio-bibliographical critical sourcebook|website=bepl.ent.sirsi.net|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=List of biographical dictionaries of women writers in English|date=2019-03-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_biographical_dictionaries_of_women_writers_in_English&oldid=889343862|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n*''A Loving Testimony: Remembering Loved Ones Lost to AIDS,'' Crossing Press (1995)\n*''Cabbage and Bones: An Anthology of Irish-American Women's Fiction'', Holt Paperbacks (1997)\n*''Touching Fire: Erotic Writings by Women'', Running Press (1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-88184-527-3|title=Touching Fire: Erotic Writings by Women |website=www.publishersweekly.com|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n*''Queer View Mirror 2: Lesbian and Gay Short Fiction'', Arsenal Pulp Press (2002)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quillandquire.c