8562-1}}\n|-\n|93\n|''Thin Air''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|New Earth}}'', Book 5)}}\n|Kristine Kathryn Rusch and Dean Wesley Smith\n| rowspan=\"2\" |August 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-78577-X}}\n|-\n|94\n|''Challenger''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|New Earth}}'', Book 6)}}\n|Diane Carey\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04298-X}}\n|-\n|95\n|''Swordhunt'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|Rihannsu}}'', Book 3)}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Diane Duane\n| rowspan=\"2\" |October 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04209-2}}\n|-\n|96\n|''Honor Blade'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|Rihannsu}}'', Book 4)}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04210-6}}\n|-\n|97\n|''In the Name of Honor''\n|Dayton Ward\n|January 20, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1225-7}}\n|}\n\n==== Film tie-ins for children (1982\u20131986) ====\nPublished by Pocket Books. Some printings are badged as Wanderer, Minstrel, Archway, or Simon & Schuster Just for Boys.\n{{Further|List of Star Trek fictional works#Film tie-ins}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title ^\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek II: Short Stories'' (anthology)\n| rowspan=\"2\" |William Rotsler\n|December 1982\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-46390-X}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek III: Short Stories'' (anthology)\n|May 1984\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-50139-9}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Worlds Apart'' (1984\u20131987) ====\n'''''Star Trek: Worlds Apart''''' is a miniseries retroactively applied to two novels by [[John M. Ford]]. The series name first appeared on 1999 reprints of the novels which included new cover designs. The novels do not form a coherent storyline.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''The Final Reflection''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 16)}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |John M. Ford\n|May 1984\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-47388-3}}\n|-\n|2\n|''How Much for Just the Planet?''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 36)}}\n|October 1987\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-62998-0}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Rihannsu'' (1984-2006) ====\n{{Main|Star Trek: Rihannsu}}\n'''''Star Trek: Rihannsu''''' miniseries explores the [[Romulan]] culture during the ''Original Series'' era. Written by [[Diane Duane]] and [[Peter Morwood]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''My Enemy, My Ally''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 18)}}\n|Diane Duane\n|July 1984\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-50285-9}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The Romulan Way''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 35)}}\n|Diane Duane and Peter Morwood\n|August 1987\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-63498-4}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Swordhunt''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 95)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Diane Duane\n| rowspan=\"2\" |October 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04209-2}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Honor Blade''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 96)}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04210-6}}\n|-\n|5\n|''The Empty Chair''\n|November 28, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0891-0}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''The Bloodwing Voyages'' (omnibus){{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|Rihannsu}}'', Books 1{{Snd}}4)}}\n|Diane Duane and Peter Morwood\n|December 19, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-2577-7}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Fortunes of War'' (1986) ====\n'''''Star Trek: Fortunes of War''''' is a miniseries retroactively applied to two linked novels by [[Diane Carey]]. The series name first appeared on 1999 reprints of the novels which included new cover designs. Additional novels were planned by Carey which remain unpublished.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite magazine|last=Hall|first=Wanda J.|date=October 1990|editor-last=McDonnell|editor-first=David|title=Beyond the Final Frontier|magazine=[[Starlog]]|issue=159|pages=84\u201385|issn=0191-4626}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Dreadnought!''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 29)}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Diane Carey\n|May 1986\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-61873-3}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Battlestations!''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 31)}}\n|November 1986\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-63267-1}}\n|}\n\n==== Original novels (1986\u2013present) ====\nIncludes hardcover and paperback releases. Novels released since 2013 include the ''Original Series'' subtitle on the cover design.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Enterprise: The First Adventure''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=enterprise}}\n|Vonda N. McIntyre\n|September 1986\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-62581-0}}\n|-\n|''Strangers from the Sky''\n|Margaret Wander Bonanno\n|July 1987\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-64049-6}}\n|-\n|''Final Frontier''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=final}}\n|Diane Carey\n|January 1988\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-64752-0}}\n|-\n|''[[Spock's World]]'' \u2020\u2021\n|Diane Duane\n|September 1988\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-66851-X}}\n|-\n|''Prime Directive'' \u2020\u2021\n|Judith and Garfield Reeves Stevens\n|September 1990\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-70772-8}}\n|-\n|''Probe'' \u2020\n|Margaret Wander Bonanno{{Efn-lg|As by Margaret Wander Bonanno. Uncredited rewrite by Gene DeWeese.}}\n|April 1992\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-72420-7}}\n|-\n|''Best Destiny'' \u2020\n|Diane Carey\n|November 1992\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-79587-2}}\n|-\n|''Shadows on the Sun'' \u2020\n|Michael Jan Friedman\n|August 1993\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-71832-0}}\n|-\n|''[[Sarek (novel)|Sarek]]'' \u2020\u2021\n|A. C. Crispin\n|March 1994\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-79561-9}}\n|-\n|''Vulcan's Forge'' \u2020\n|Josepha Sherman and Susan Shwartz\n|August 1997\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00926-5}}\n|-\n|''Treaty's Law'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|Day of Honor}}'', Book 4)}}\n|Kristine Kathryn Rusch and Dean Wesley Smith\n|October 1997\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00424-7}}\n|-\n|''War Dragons'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|The Captain's Table}}'', Book 1)}}\n|L.A. Graf{{Efn-lg|As by James T. Kirk and Hikaru Sulu, told in their own words, as recorded by L.A. Graf.|name=kirksulu}}\n|June 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01463-3}}\n|-\n|''Where Sea Meets Sky'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|The Captain's Table}}'', Book 6)}}\n|Jerry Oltion{{Efn-lg|As by Christopher Pike, told in his own words, as recorded by Jerry Oltion.|name=pike}}\n|October 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02400-0}}\n|-\n|''Mission t