 omnibus edition was published in 2002. The novels were partially adapted as [[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine: The Fallen|''The Fallen'']] (2000), a [[third-person shooter]] video game developed by [[The Collective (company)|The Collective]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''The Fall of Terok Nor''\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens\n| rowspan=\"2\" |March 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02401-9}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The War of the Prophets''\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02402-7}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Inferno''\n|April 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02403-5}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''Millennium'' (omnibus)\n|January 2, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4249-0}}\n|}\n\n==== Relaunch novels (2000\u20132017) ====\nInterlinked novels set after the episode \"[[What You Leave Behind]]\":\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Lives of Dax''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|Originally published as ''Star Trek: The Lives of Dax''. Second printing included the rounded ''Star Trek: Deep Space Nine'' mark used for the relaunch series.}} (anthology)\n|Marco Palmieri, ed\n|December 1999\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02840-5}}\n|-\n|''A Stitch in Time''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Deep Space Nine}}'', Book 27)}}\n|Andrew J. Robinson\n|May 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-03885-0}}\n|-\n|''Avatar'', Book 1 \u2021\n| rowspan=\"2\" |S.D. Perry\n| rowspan=\"2\" |May 1, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-0050-X}}\n|-\n|''Avatar'', Book 2 \u2021\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-0051-8}}\n|-\n|''Abyss''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|name=relaunch}} \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|Section 31}}'', Book 4)}}\n|David Weddle and Jeffrey Lang\n|June 26, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-77483-2}}\n|-\n|''Demons of Air and Darkness''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|name=relaunch}} \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|Gateways}}'', Book 4)}}\n|Keith DeCandido\n|August 28, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1852-2}}\n|-\n|''Rising Son''\n|S.D. Perry\n|December 31, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4838-3}}\n|-\n|''The Left Hand of Destiny'', Book 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" |J. G. Hertzler and Jeffrey Lang\n|Ma