ble|Captain's Table}}\n'''''Star Trek: The Captain's Table''''' crossover miniseries is narrated by various starship captains during their visits to a trans-dimensional bar called The Captain's Table. An omnibus edition was published in 2000. A short story anthology of linked stories was published in 2005. ''War Dragons'' and ''Where Sea Meets Sky'' are ''Star Trek'' novels, but neither include the ''Original Series'' subtitle.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''War Dragons''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}''{{--)}}}}\n|L.A. Graf{{Efn-lg|name=kirksulu}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |June 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01463-3}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Dujonian's Hoard''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|The Next Generation}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Michael Jan Friedman{{Efn-lg|name=picard}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01465-X}}\n|-\n|3\n|''The Mist''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Deep Space Nine}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Dean Wesley Smith and Kristine Kathryn Rusch{{Efn-lg|name=sisko}}\n|July 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01471-4}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Fire Ship''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Voyager}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Diane Carey{{Efn-lg|name=janeway}}\n|July 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01467-6}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Once Burned''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|New Frontier}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Peter David{{Efn-lg|name=calhoun}}\n|October 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02078-1}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Where Sea Meets Sky''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Jerry Oltion{{Efn-lg|name=pike}}\n|October 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02400-0}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''The Captain's Table'' (omnibus)\n|L.A. Graf, et al.{{Efn-ua|''The Captain's Table'' (2000) by L.A. Graf, Michael Jan Friedman, Dean Wesley Smith and Kristine Kathryn Rusch, Diane Carey, Peter David, Jerry Oltion.}}\n|March 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04052-9}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Dominion War'' (1998-2004) ====\n{{Anchor|The Dominion War|Dominion War}}\n'''''Star Trek: The Dominion War''''' crossover miniseries depicts events leading up to the [[Dominion War]]. The first and third novels focus on the crew of the {{USS|Enterprise|NCC-1701-E|6}}, while the second and fourth novels are novelizations of a seven-episode arc from ''Deep Space Nine''{{'s}} sixth and seventh seasons. The novels contain additional characters and situations created by the authors.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Bowden|first=Steve|last2=Nansi|first2=Salman A.|date=August 1999|editor-last=Nemecek|editor-first=Larry|title=What You Leave Behind: Novelizing the Finale|magazine=Star Trek Communicator|issue=124|page=86|issn=1080-3793}}</ref> ''The Battle for Betazed'' (2002), by Charlotte Douglas and Susan Kearney, and the short story anthology ''Tales of the Dominion War'' (2004), are linked to the series.\n{{See|Dominion War#Tie-in media}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Behind Enemy Lines''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|The Next Generation}}''{{--)}}}}\n|John Vornholt\n| rowspan=\"2\" |November 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02499-X}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Call to Arms''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Deep Space Nine}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Diane Carey\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02497-3}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Tunnel Through the Stars''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|The Next Generation}}''{{--)}}}}\n|John Vornholt\n| rowspan=\"2\" |December 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02500-7}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Sacrifice of Angels''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Deep Space Nine}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Diane Carey\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02498-1}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Section 31'' (2001\u20132017) ====\n{{Main|Star Trek: Section 31}}\n'''''Star Trek: Section 31''''' crossover miniseries was inspired by the clandestine, paramilitary organization introduced in the ''Deep Space Nine'' episode \"[[Inquisition (Star Trek: Deep Space Nine)|Inquisition]]\". The series was relaunched in 2014, originally as part of the ''Deep Space Nine'' book line.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Rogue''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|The Next Generation}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Andy Mangels and Michael A. Martin\n| rowspan=\"2\" |May 22, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-77477-8}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Shadow''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Voyager}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Dean Wesley Smith and Kristine Kathryn Rusch\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-77478-6}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Cloak''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}''{{--)}}}}\n|S. D. Perry\n| rowspan=\"2\" |June 26, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-77471-9}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Abyss'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Deep Space Nine}}''{{--)}}}}\n|David Weddle and Jeffrey Lang\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-77483-2}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Gateways'' (2001) ====\n{{Anchor|Gateways}}\n'''''Star Trek: Gateways''''' crossover miniseries explores various Starfleet crews with trans-dimensional gateways left behind by the ancient [[Iconian]] race. The series was created by [[Robert Greenberger]] and [[John J. Ordover]]. The series concluded with the short story anthology ''What Lay Beyond'' (2001). An omnibus edition was announced at the Shore Leave convention in 2001, but was never published.{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''One Small Step''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Susan Wright\n| rowspan=\"2\" |July 31, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1854-9}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Chainmail''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Challenger}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Diane Carey\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1855-7}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Doors into Chaos''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|The Next Generation}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Robert Greenberger\n| rowspan=\"2\" |August 28, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1856-5}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Demons of Air and Darkness'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Deep Space Nine}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Keith DeCandido\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1852-2}}\n|-\n|5\n|''No Man's Land''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Voyager}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Christie Golden\n| rowspan=\"2\" |October 2, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1857-3}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Cold Wars''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|New Frontier}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Peter David\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04242-4}}\n|-\n|7\n|''What Lay Beyond'' \u2020 (anthology)\n|John J. Ordover, ed.{{Efn-ua|''What Lay Beyond'' (2001) (''{{Pink|Gateways}}'', Book 7) by John J. Ordover, editor, with Diane Carey, Peter David, Keith DeCandido, Christie Golden, Robert Greenberger, and Susan Wright.|name=whatlay}}\n|October 30, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-3112-X}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''Here There Be Monsters''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|S.C.E.}}'', {{Abbr|No.|Number}} 10)}}\n|Keith DeCandido\n|November 15, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2877-3}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Destiny'' (2008\u20132012) ====\n{{Anchor|Destiny}}\n'''''Star Trek: Destiny''''' crossover miniseries explores the origin of the [[Borg]], and the Federation's response to an invasion by them. Written by David Mack. Followed by ''Typhon Pact'' (2010\u20132013). An omnibus edition was published in 2012.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Gods of Night''\n| rowspan=\"4\" |David Mack\n|September 30, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-5171-3}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Mere Mortals''\n|October 28, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-5172-0}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Lost Souls''\n|November 25, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-5175-1}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''Destiny'' (omnibus)\n|March 13, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-5724-1}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Voyager'' (1995\u2013present) ===\n{{Main|List of Star Trek: Voyager novels}}\n[[File:Star Trek VOY logo.svg|thumb|alt=Star Trek: Voyager logo.]]\n'''''Star Trek: Voyager''''' book line is based on the [[Star Trek: Voyager|television series of the same name]]. The book line was relaunched with the publication of ''Homecoming'' (2003), by [[Christie Golden]].\n\n==== Episode novelizations (1995\u20132001) ====\nBased on select episodes from the television series.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Caretaker''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Voyager}}'', Book 1)}}\n|L.A. Graf\n|February 1995\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-51914-X}}\n|-\n|''Flashback''\n|Diane Carey\n|October 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00383-6}}\n|-\n|''Day of Honor''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|name=day}} \u2021{