ds Above''\n|September 30, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1858-1}}\n|-\n|14\n|''Stone and Anvil'' \u2020\n|October 28, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2957-5}}\n|-\n|15\n|''After the Fall'' \u2020\n|November 30, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9184-X}}\n|-\n|16\n|''Missing in Action'' \u2020\n|February 28, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-1080-X}}\n|-\n|17\n|''Treason''\n|April 14, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-0-7434-2961-0}}\n|-\n|18\n|''Blind Man's Bluff''\n|April 26, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-0-7434-2960-3}}\n|}\n\n==== Original novels (1998\u20132001) ====\nIncludes hardcover and paperback releases:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''New Frontier'' \u2020 (omnibus){{Indent|2}}{{Small|(Books 1{{Snd}}4)}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Peter David\n|February 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01978-3}}\n|-\n|''Once Burned''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lg|As by Mackenzie Calhoun, in his own words, as recorded by Peter David.|name=calhoun}} \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|The Captain's Table}}'', Book 5)}}\n|October 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02078-1}}\n|-\n|''Cold Wars''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|Gateways}}'', Book 6)}}\n|October 2, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04242-4}}\n|-\n|''No Limits'' (anthology)\n|October 21, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-7707-3}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Excalibur'' (2000) ====\n'''''Star Trek: New Frontier'''{{Snd}}'''Excalibur''''' miniseries follows the crew after the destruction of the ''Excalibur'', and the apparent death of Calhoun. David originally proposed each novel title contain the prefix ''Excalibur'', such as ''Excalibur: Restoration''. Thought it was abandoned at the time of publication, some marketing materials and library catalogs followed this convention.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Requiem''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|New Frontier}}'', Book 9)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Peter David\n| rowspan=\"2\" |September 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04238-6}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Renaissance''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|New Frontier}}'', Book 10)}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04239-4}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Restoration'' \u2020{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|New Frontier}}'', Book 11)}}\n|November 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04243-2}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Returned'' (2015) ====\n'''''Star Trek: New Frontier'''{{Snd}}'''The Returned''''' miniseries explores the aftermath of events depicted in ''Blind Man's Bluff'' (2011). Published as ebook exclusives by Pocket Star.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.startrek.com/article/the-returned-out-this-summer|title=The Returned: Out This Summer|date=2015-03-07|website=StarTrek.com|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title \u25ca\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN (ebook)\n|-\n|''The Returned'', Part 1\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Peter David\n|July 6, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-9092-3}}\n|-\n|''The Returned'', Part 2\n|August 3, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-9093-0}}\n|-\n|''The Returned'', Part 3\n|September 7, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-9095-4}}\n|}\n\n=== Short fiction (1998\u20132016) ===\nCollections of short fiction from various series:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Editors(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Enterprise Logs''\n|Carol Greenburg\n|June 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-03579-7}}\n|-\n|''The Amazing Stories''\n|John J. Ordover\n|August 20, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4915-0}}\n|-\n|''Tales of the Dominion War''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Keith DeCandido\n|August 3, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9171-8}}\n|-\n|''Tales from the Captain's Table''\n|June 14, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0520-2}}\n|-\n|''Seven Deadly Sins''\n|Margaret Clark\n|March 16, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-0944-1}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Strange New Worlds'' (1998\u20132016) ====\n{{Main|Star Trek: Strange New Worlds}}\n'''''Star Trek: Strange New Worlds''''' is a short story anthology series edited by Dean Wesley Smith. Each volume collected fan-submitted stories, similar to Bantam Books' ''The New Voyages'' (1976\u20131978).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds''\n| rowspan=\"10\" |Dean Wesley Smith, ed.\n|July 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01446-3}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds II''\n|May 1999\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02692-5}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds III''\n|May 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-03652-1}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds IV''\n|May 1, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1131-5}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds V''\n|May 28, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-3778-0}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds VI''\n|June 17, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6753-1}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds VII''\n|June 29, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-8780-X}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds 8''\n|July 19, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0345-5}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds 9''\n|August 22, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-2048-1}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds 10''\n|July 10, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-4438-8}}\n|-\n|''Strange New Worlds 2016'' \u25ca\n|Neil Bryant, et al.{{Efn-ua|''Strange New Worlds 2016'' (2016) by Neil Bryant, Gary Piserchio and Frank Tagader, Kelli Fitzpatrick, Chris Chaplin, Michael Turner, Nancy Debretsion, Derek Tyler Attico, Roger McCoy, John Coffren, and Kristen McQuinn.}}\n|October 3, 2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-6158-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Corps of Engineers'' (2000\u20132010) ===\n{{Anchor|Starfleet Corps of Engineers|Corps of Engineers|SCE|S.C.E.}}\n'''''Star Trek: Corps of Engineers''''' follows the crew of the {{Ship|USS|da Vinci|NCC-81623|6|wl=no}}. The series was marketed as ebook exclusives on various platforms, and were later collected into print bind-ups with similar titles, but a different numbering scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unreality-sf.net/2010/10/10/miracle-workers-remembering-sce-3/|title=Roundtable: Miracle Workers \u2013 remembering S.C.E. (Part 3)|last=Deffner|first=Jens|date=2010-10-10|website=unreality-sf.net|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-18}}</ref> The series was originally published as '''''Star Trek: Starfleet Corps of Engineers'''''.\n\n==== Original novellas (2000\u20132006) ====\nNovellas are numbered 1 through 66. Many were also published as part of multipart series, such as ''Foundations'' (2002), ''Wildfire'' (2003), and ''What's Past'' (2006). All novellas were later collected in omnibus editions with a different numbering scheme. The series name was abbreviated as '''''S.C.E.''''' on the digital covers.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title \u25ca\u2021\n!Author(s)\n!Date{{Efn|name=streetdate}}\n!ISBN (ebook)\n|-\n|1\n|''The Belly of the Beast''\n|Dean Wesley Smith\n|August 8, 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1901-4}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Fatal Error''\n|Keith DeCandido\n|September 13, 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1902-2}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Hard Crash''\n|Christie Golden\n|October 8, 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1903-0}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Interphase'', Book 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Dayon Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|February 28, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2882-X}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Interphase'', Book 2\n|March 28, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2871-4}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Cold Fusion''\n|Keith DeCandido\n|July 27, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2875-7}}\n|-\n|7\n|''Invincible'', Book 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Keith DeCandido and David Mack\n|August 15, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2872-2}}\n|-\n|8\n|''Invincible'', Book 2\n|September 26, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2873-0}}\n|-\n|9\n|''The Riddled Post''\n|Aaron Rosenberg\n|October 12, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2876-5}}\n|-\n|10\n|''Here There Be Monsters''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Pink|Gateways}}''{{--)}}}}\n|Keith DeCandido\n|November 15, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2877-3}}\n|-\n|11\n|''Ambush''\n|Dave Galanter\n|December 14, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2878-1}}\n|-\n|12\n|''Some Assembly Required''\n|Scott Ciencin and Dan Jolley\n|January 15, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2879-X}}\n|-\n|13\n|''No Surrender''\n|Jeff Mariotte\n|February 11, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2880-3}}\n|-\n|14\n|''Caveat Emptor''\n|Ian Edginton and Mike Collins\n|March 15, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2874-9}}\n|-\n|15\n|''Past Life''\n|Robert Greenberger\n|April 15, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2881-1}}\n|-\n|16\n|''Oaths''\n|Glenn Hauman\n|May 15, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-5671-8}}\n|-\n|17\n|''Foundations'', Book 1\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Kevin Dilmore and Dayton Ward\n|June 14, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-5672-6}}\n|-\n|18\n|''Foundations'', Book 2\n|July 15, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|