NT|0-7434-9658-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Titan'' (2005\u20132017) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Titan}}\n'''''Star Trek: Titan''''' is flagship series set aboard the {{Ship|USS|Titan|wl=no}}, under the command of [[William Riker]]. The starship ''Titan'' was introduced in ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis|Nemesis]]'' (2002). Not all novels are numbered by Simon & Schuster.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Taking Wing''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Michael A. Martin and Andy Mangels\n|March 29, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9627-2}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The Red King''\n|September 27, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9628-0}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Orion's Hounds''\n|Christopher L. Bennett\n|December 27, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0950-X}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Sword of Damocles''\n|Geoffrey Thorne\n|November 27, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-2694-0}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Over a Torrent Sea''\n|Christopher L. Bennett\n|February 24, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-9497-0}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Synthesis''\n|James Swallow\n|October 27, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-0914-4}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{Unknown|}}\n|''Fallen Gods''\n|Michael A. Martin\n|July 31, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-6062-3}}\n|-\n|''Absent Enemies'' \u25ca\n|John Jackson Miller\n|February 24, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-6299-9}}\n|-\n|''Sight Unseen''\n|James Swallow\n|September 29, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-8316-1}}\n|-\n|''Fortune of War''\n|David Mack\n|November 28, 2017\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-5200-9}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Vanguard'' (2005\u20132012) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Vanguard}}\n'''''Star Trek: Vanguard''''' is a flagship concept series concurrent with the events of ''Star Trek''. Set aboard {{Ship|Starbase 47|Vanguard|wl=no}} on the edge of an unexplored region of space known as the Taurus Reach. Conceived and written by Dayton Ward, Kevin Dilmore, and David Mack. The novella, ''Distant Early Warning'' (2006), by Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore, is a prequel to ''Vanguard''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Harbinger''\n|David Mack\n|July 26, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0774-4}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Summon the Thunder''\n|Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|June 27, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-2400-2}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Reap the Whirlwind''\n|David Mack\n|May 22, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-3414-3}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Open Secrets''\n|Dayton Ward\n|April 28, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-4792-1}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Precipice''\n|David Mack\n|November 24, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-3011-7}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Declassified''\n|Dayton Ward, et al.{{Efn-ua|''Declassified'' (''{{Teal|Vanguard}}'', Book 6) (2011) by Dayton Ward, Kevin Dilmore, Marco Palmieri, and David Mack.}}\n|June 28, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0691-1}}\n|-\n|7\n|''What Judgments Come''\n|Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|September 27, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0863-2}}\n|-\n|8\n|''Storming Heaven''\n|David Mack\n|March 27, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-5070-9}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''In Tempest's Wake'' \u25ca\n|Dayton Ward\n|October 2, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-9589-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Mirror Universe'' (2007\u20132009) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Mirror Universe''''' explores the [[Mirror Universe]] introduced in ''Star Trek'' episode \"[[Mirror, Mirror (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Mirror, Mirror]]\". ''Glass Empires'' (2007) and ''Obsidian Alliances'' (2007) are collections of three novellas each. ''Shards and Shadows'' (2009) is a short story anthology. ''The Sorrows of Empire'' (2009) was expanded from a novella collected in ''Glass Empires''. ''Fearful Symmetry'' (2008) and ''The Soul Key'' (2009), by Olivia Wood, and ''Disavowed'' (2014), by David Mack, are linked to the series. Early solicitations of Wood's novels included the ''Mirror Universe'' logo, in addition to the ''Deep Space Nine'' marquee.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Glass Empires''\n|Michael Sussman, et al.{{Efn-ua|''Glass Empires'' (''{{Teal|Mirror Universe}}''{{--)}} (2007) by Michael Sussman, with Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore, David Mack, and Greg Cox.}}\n|February 20, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-2459-5}}\n|-\n|''Obsidian Alliances''\n|Keith DeCandido, Peter David, and Sara Shaw{{Efn-lg|Sara Shaw is pseudonymous with [[David Alan Mack|David Mack]].}}\n|March 20, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-2471-7}}\n|-\n|''Shards and Shadows'' (anthology)\n|Marco Palmieri and Margaret Clark, eds.\n|January 6, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-5850-7}}\n|-\n|''Sorrows of the Empire''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |David Mack\n|December 29, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-5516-5}}\n|-\n|''Rise Like Lions''\n|November 29, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0719-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Academy'' (2007) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Academy''''' was intended to be a new flagship series featuring a young Midshipman [[James T. Kirk|Jim Kirk]]. ''Trial Run'', the second in the series, was announced but was never published.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Collision Course|last=Shatner|first=William|last2=Reeves-Stevens|first2=Judith|last3=Reeves-Stevens|first3=Garfield|date=2007-10-16|publisher=[[Pocket Books]]|isbn=9781416503965|series=Star Trek: Academy|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/startrekacademy00shat/page/452 452]|author-link=William Shatner|author-link2=Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens|author-link3=Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens|url=https://archive.org/details/startrekacademy00shat/page/452}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Collision Course'' \u2020\n|William Shatner,{{Indent|2}}with Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens\n|October 16, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-0396-5}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Excelsior'' (2007) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Excelsior''''' was a flagship series concept set aboard the {{Ship|USS|Excelsior|NCC-2000|4|wl=no}}, under the command of Captain [[Hikaru Sulu]]. Only one novel has been published, which is marketed as part of the ''Original Series'' book line by Simon & Schuster.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Forged in Fire''\n|Michael A. Martin and Andy Mangels\n|December 26, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-4716-7}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Klingon Empire'' (2008) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Klingon Empire''''' is a relaunch of I.K.S. ''Gorkon'' (2003\u20132005).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''A Burning House''\n|Keith DeCandido\n|January 29, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-5647-3}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Myriad Universes'' (2008\u20132010) ===\n{{Anchor|Myriad Universes}}\n'''''Star Trek: Myriad Universes''''' novella series explores alternate realties, and how those settings affect the analogues of characters from various television series and films. The novellas are collected in three numbered volumes. ''The Last Generation'' comics miniseries, by Andrew Steven Harris and published by [[IDW Publishing|IDW]] from 2008 to 2009, ties into ''Infinity's Prism'' (2008) and ''Echoes and Refractions'' (2008).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Infinity's Prism''\n|William Leisner, Christopher L. Bennett, and James Swallow\n|July 22, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-7180-3}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Echoes and Refractions''\n|Geoff Trowbridge, Keith DeCandido, and Chris Roberson\n|August 12, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-7181-0}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Shattered Light''\n|David R. George III, et al.{{Efn-ua|''Shattered Light'' (''{{Teal|Myriad Universes}}'', Book 3) (2010) by David R. George II, Steve Mollman and Michael Schuster, and Scott Pearson.}}\n|December 14, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-4841-9}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Kelvin'' Timeline (2009\u20132013) ===\n[[File:Star Trek movie logo.svg|thumb|alt=Star Trek (2009) logo.]]\nBased on ''[[Star Trek (film)|Star Trek]]'' (2009) film and its sequels.\n\n==== Film novelizations (2009\u20132013) ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Alan Dean Foster\n|May 12, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-5886-9}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Into Darkness''\n|May 21, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-1648-0}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Starfleet Academy'' (2010\u20132012) ====\n'''''Star Trek: Starfleet Academy''''' young adult miniseries explores the lives of the ''Enterprise'' crew as [[Starfleet Academy]] cadets. The series depicts the timeline of events from the ''Kelvin'' Timeline films, and differs greatly from a similarly named series published in 1996.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title \u2020\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''The Delta Anomaly''\n|Rick Barba\n|November 2, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4424-1409-9}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The Edge''\n|Rudy Josephs\n|December 28, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4424-1408-2}}\n|-\n|3\n|''The Gemini Agent''\n|Rick Barba\n|June 28, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4424-1961-2}}\n|-\n|4\n|''The Assassination Game''\n|Alan Gratz and Rick Barba\n|June 26, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4424-2058-8}}\n|}\n\n==== Original novels (2020) ====\nThe following novels were announced at the ''Star Trek'' Las Vegas 2019 convention.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://blog.trekcore.com/2019/08/2020-star-trek-book-news-star-trek-picard-kelvin-timeline/|title=STAR TREK: PICARD and Kelvin Timeline Tie-In Books Lead 2020 Trek Publishing Announcements|date=2019-08-01|website=TrekCore.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref> They were previously scheduled for release in 2010.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://trekmovie.com/2010/01/14/pocket-books-holding-off-on-star-trek-movie-tie-ins-4-novels-pulled-from-summer-2010/|title=Pocket Books 'Holding Off' On Star Trek Movie Tie-ins \u2013 4 Novels Pulled From Summer 2010|last=Pascale|first=Anthony|date=2010-01-14|website=TrekMovie.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Unsettling Stars''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|''The Unsettling Stars'' (2020), by Alan Dean Foster, was previously marketed as ''Refugees'' and ''The Order of Peace''.|name=unsettling}} (forthcoming)\n|Alan Dean Foster\n|April 14, 2020<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/The-Unsettling-Stars/Alan-Dean-Foster/Star-Trek/9781982140601|title=The Unsettling Stars|last=Foster|first=Alan Dean|date=2020-04-14|publisher=[[Pocket Books]]|isbn=9781982140601|series=Star Trek|location=New York|language=en|author-link=Alan Dean Foster|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-4060-1}}\n|-\n|''More Beautiful Than Death'' (forthcoming)\n|David Mack\n|August 11, 2020<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/9781982140625|title=More Beautiful Than Death|last=Mack|first=David|date=2020-08-11|publisher=[[Pocket Books| Pocket Books/Star Trek]]|isbn=9781982140625|series=Star Trek|location=New York|language=en|author-link=David Alan Mack|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-4062-5}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Star Trek Online'' (2010) ===\n'''''Star Trek Online''''' is based on the [[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]] [[Star Trek Online|of the same name]]. ''The Needs of the Many'' (2010), by [[Michael A. Martin]], expanded on the timeline of the events explored by players of the game. It is unclear if additional novels will be published.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Needs of the Many''\n|Michael A. Martin\n|March 30, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-8657-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Typhon Pact'' (2010\u20132013) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Typhon Pact}}\n'''''Star Trek: Typhon Pact''''' series explores the political chaos following the destruction of the Borg in ''Destiny'' (2008). ''A Singular Destiny'' (2009), by Keith DeCandido, introduced the Typhon Pact as the Federation's primary antagonist. Many storylines conclude in ''The Fall'' (2013\u201314). The novels are numbered by Simon & Schuster.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Zero Sum Game''\n|David Mack\n|October 26, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-6079-4}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Seize the Fire''\n|Michael A. Martin\n|November 30, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-6782-3}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Rough Beasts of Empire''\n|David R. George III\n|December 28, 2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-6081-7}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Paths of Disharmony''\n|Dayton Ward\n|January 25, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-6083-1}}\n|-\n|5\n|''The Struggle Within'' \u25ca\n|Christopher L. Bennett\n|October 4, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-5142-3}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Plagues of Night'' \u2021\n| rowspan=\"2\" |David R. George III\n|May 29, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-4955-0}}\n|-\n|7\n|''Raise the Dawn'' \u2021\n|June 26, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-4956-7}}\n|-\n|8\n|''Brinkmanship'' \u2021\n|Una McCormack\n|September 25, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-8782-8}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''The Khitomer Accords Saga'' \u25ca (omnibus){{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Typhon Pact}}'', Books 6{{Snd}}8)}}\n|David R. George III and Una McCormack\n|January 22, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-3334-0}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Department of Temporal Investigations'' (2011\u20132017) ===\n{{Anchor|Department of Temporal Investigations|DTI}}\n'''''Star Trek: Department of Temporal Investigations''''', often abbreviated as '''''D.T.I.''''', is based on the fictional Federation agency responsible for investigating time travel incidents. The protagonists, Lucsly and Dulmur, were introduced in the ''Deep Space Nine'' episode \"[[Trials and Tribble-ations]]\". The novels are not numbered. ''Forgotten History'' (2012) was collected in ''The Continuing Missions'', {{Abbr|Vol.|Volume}} 1{{Efn-lr|name=continuing}} (2013).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Watching the Clock''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Christopher L. Bennett\n|April 26, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0625-6}}\n|-\n|''Forgotten History'' \u2021\n|April 24, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-5725-8}}\n|-\n|''The Collectors'' \u25ca\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Christopher L. Bennett\n|December 8, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-8259-1}}\n|-\n|''Time Lock'' \u25ca\n|December 5, 2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-2334-4}}\n|-\n|''Shield of the Gods'' \u25ca\n|June 9, 2017\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-6488-0}}\n|}\n\n=== ''The Fall'' (2013\u201314) ===\n{{Anchor|The Fall}}\n'''''Star Trek: The Fall''''' is a continuation of ''Typhon Pact'' (2010\u20132013). Events in the novels occur over a two-month period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://trekcore.com/blog/2013/09/exclusive-una-mccormack-interview/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Una McCormack Interview|date=2013-09-18|website=trekcore.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Revelation and Dust''\n|David R. George III\n|August 27, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-2217-7}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The Crimson Shadow''\n|Una McCormack\n|September 24, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-2220-7}}\n|-\n|3\n|''A Ceremony of Losses''\n|David Mack\n|October 29, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-2224-5}}\n|-\n|4\n|''The Poisoned Chalice''\n|James Swallow\n|November 26, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-2222-1}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Peaceable Kingdoms''\n|Dayton Ward\n|December 31, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-1899-6}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Seekers'' (2014\u201315) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Seekers''''' is a continuation of ''Vanguard'' (2005\u20132012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daytonward.wordpress.com/2013/08/02/announcing-star-trek-seekers/|title=Announcing STAR TREK: SEEKERS!|last=Ward|first=Dayton|authorlink=Dayton Ward|date=2013-08-03|website=The Fog of Ward.|language=en|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Second Nature''\n|David Mack\n|July 22, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-5307-2}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Point of Divergence''\n|Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|August 26, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-5726-1}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Long Shot''\n|David Mack\n|July 28, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-5309-6}}\n|-\n|4\n|''All That's Left''\n|Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|October 27, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-9860-8}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Section 31'' relaunch (2014\u20132017) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Section 31''''' miniseries is a relaunch of the ''Section 31'' (2001) crossover miniseries. The novels are linked to other ''Deep Space Nine'' and the ''Next Generation'' relaunch novels. The series is marketed as part of the ''Deep Space Nine'' book line by Simon & Schuster. Many plots continue in ''Collateral Damage'' (2019), also by David Mack.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Disavowed''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |David Mack\n|October 28, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-5308-9}}\n|-\n|''Control''\n|March 28, 2017\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-5170-5}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Prey'' (2016) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Prey''''' follows the exploits of a company of thieves. Includes characters from ''Star Trek'', ''Next Generation'', and ''Titan''. Written by [[John Jackson Miller]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Hell's Heart''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |John Jackson Miller\n|September 27, 2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-1579-0}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The Jackal's Trick''\n|October 25, 2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-1580-6}}\n|-\n|3\n|''The Hall of Heroes''\n|November 29, 2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-1603-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Discovery'' (2017\u2013present) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Discovery#Novels}}\n[[File:Star Trek Discovery logo.svg|thumb|alt=Star Trek: Discovery logo.]]\n'''''Star Trek: Discovery''''' book line is based on the [[Star Trek: Discovery|television series of the same name]], with each volume following the continuity of the television series closely.<ref>{{Cite podcast|url=http://www.trek.fm/literary-treks/206|title=Almost Too Much Latitude|website=Literary Treks|number=206|publisher=Trek.fm|date=2017-10-08|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> The novels are numbered by Simon & Schuster; however, not all printings include a number stamp.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/9781982113315|title=The Enterprise War|last=Miller|first=John Jackson|date=2019-07-30|publisher=[[Pocket Books|Pocket Books/Star Trek]]|isbn=9781982113315|series=Star Trek: Discovery|volume=5|location=New York|language=en|author-link=John Jackson Miller|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Desperate Hours''\n|David Mack\n|September 26, 2017\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-6457-6}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Drastic Measures''\n|Dayton Ward\n|February 6, 2018\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-7174-1}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Fear Itself''\n|James Swallow\n|June 5, 2018\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-6659-4}}\n|-\n|4\n|''The Way to the Stars''\n|Una McCormack\n|January 8, 2019\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-0475-7}}\n|-\n|5\n|''The Enterprise War''\n|John Jackson Miller\n|July 30, 2019\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-1331-5}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Dead Endless''\n|Dave Galanter\n|December 17, 2019\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-2384-0}}\n|-\n|7\n|''Die Standing'' (forthcoming)\n|John Jackson Miller\n|July 14, 2020<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Miller|first=John Jackson|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/9781982136291|title=Die Standing|date=2020-07-14|publisher=[[Pocket Books|Pocket Books/Star Trek]]|isbn=9781982136291|series=Star Trek: Discovery|volume=7|location=New York|language=en|author-link=John Jackson Miller|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-3629-1}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Picard'' (2020) ===\n[[File:Star Trek Picard logo.svg|thumb|alt=Star Trek: Picard logo.]]\n'''''Star Trek: Picard''''' is based on the [[Star Trek: Picard|television series of the same name]]. ''The Last Best Hope'' (2020) is a prequel to the television series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.startrek.com/news/new-star-trek-books-simon-schuster-discovery-idw|title=New 'Picard' Prequel Books Revealed at STLV Publishing Panel|date=2019-08-01|website=Star Trek|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Last Best Hope''\n|Una McCormack\n|February 11, 2020<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/9781982139445|title=The Last Best Hope|last=McCormack|first=Una|date=2020-02-11|publisher=[[Pocket Books|Pocket Books/Star Trek]]|isbn=9781982139445|series=Star Trek: Picard|location=New York|language=en|author-link=Una McCormack|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-9821-3944-5}}\n|}\n\n== Titan Books (1987\u2013present) ==\n{{Anchor|Titan Books}}\nA division of the [[Titan Publishing Group]], Titan Books reprinted Pocket and Bantam Books originals for the United Kingdom market from 1987 to 1995. [[Penguin Random House]] distributes Titan's licensed publications to the United States and Canada. Outside of North America, Titan's reprints are the most widely available editions. Many reprints include spelling changes and minor corrections to their original text to align with Titan's house style, and with [[British spelling]].\n\n=== ''Star Trek'' (reprint) (1987\u20131993) ===\nReprints of Pocket Book's '''''Star Trek''''' novels with a different number scheme:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Chain of Attack''\n|Gene DeWeese\n|March 1987\n|{{ISBNT|0-907610-85-4}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Deep Domain''\n|Howard Weinstein\n|June 1987\n|{{ISBNT|0-907610-86-2}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Dreams of the Raven''\n|Carmen Carter\n|July 1987\n|{{ISBNT|0-907610-93-5}}\n|-\n|4\n|''The Romulan Way''\n|Diane Duane and Peter Morwood\n|August 1987\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-002-2}}\n|-\n|5\n|''How Much for Just the Planet?''\n|John M. Ford\n|October 1987\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-018-9}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Bloodthirst''\n|J. M. Dillard\n|December 1987\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-039-1}}\n|-\n|7\n|''The I.D.I.C. Epidemic''\n|Jean Lorrah\n|February 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-042-1}}\n|-\n|8\n|''Yesterday's Son''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |A. C. Crispin\n|March 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-061-8}}\n|-\n|9\n|''Time for Yesterday''\n|April 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-063-4}}\n|-\n|10\n|''The Final Reflection''\n|John M. Ford\n|May 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-064-2}}\n|-\n|11\n|''Time Trap''\n|David Dvorkin\n|June 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-065-0}}\n|-\n|12\n|''The Vulcan Academy Murders''\n|Jean Lorrah\n|July 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-066-9}}\n|-\n|13\n|''The Three-Minute Universe''\n|Barbara Paul\n|August 1988\n|{{ISBNT|1-85286-068-5}}\n|-\n|14\n|