sitory]]|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.waterstones.com/book/third-class/william-shatner/judith-reeves-stevens/9781416503996|title=Third Class by William Shatner, Judith Reeves-Stevens|website=[[Waterstones]]|language=en|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Tentative Title\n!Author(s)\n!Scheduled\n!Known ISBN{{Efn|name=knownisbn}}\n|-\n|''Trial Run''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |William Shatner,{{Indent|2}}with Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens\n|''2008\u20132010''\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|-\n|''Third Class''\n|''December 31, 2019''\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-0399-6}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Kelvin'' Timeline (2010) ====\nNovels based on the ''Kelvin'' Timeline [[List of Star Trek films and television series#Reboot (Kelvin Timeline) films|film series]] which were withdrawn from publication.<ref name=\":5\" /> The titles reappeared on bookseller platforms in 2011, and again in 2014. At the ''Star Trek'' Las Vegas 2019 convention, ''More Beautiful Than Death'' and ''Refugees'' were announced as scheduled for publication in 2020.<ref name=\":14\" /> ''Refugees'' was retitled ''The Order of Peace'' in initial promotional materials, however, the finished novel will be published as ''The Unsettling Stars'' in 2020.<ref name=\":4\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Tentative Title\n!Author(s)\n!Scheduled\n!Known ISBN{{Efn|name=knownisbn}}\n|-\n|''Refugees''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|name=unsettling}}\n|Alan Dean Foster\n|''April 27, 2010''\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-7553-8}}\n|-\n|''Seek A Newer World''\n|Christopher L. Bennett\n|''May 25, 2010''\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-9816-9}}\n|-\n|''More Beautiful Than Death''\n|David Mack\n|''June 29, 2010''\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-7668-9}}\n|-\n|''The Hazard of Concealing''\n|Greg Cox\n|''July 27, 2010''\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-8414-1}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Orion Factor'' (2010\u20132014) ====\n{{Anchor|The Orion Factor|Orion Factor}}\n'''''Star Trek: The Orion Factor''''' miniseries first appeared on bookseller platforms sometime in 2009. The novels were listed as forthcoming in 2010, and again in 2012, before being withdrawn in 2014. The [[Books In Print]] electronic version includes an incomplete record for ''Song of Experience''. The series remains unpublished.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Tentative Title\n!Author\n!Scheduled\n!Known ISBN{{Efn|name=knownisbn}}\n|-\n|1\n|''Song of Innocence''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Kevin Ryan\n|''December 31, 2010''\n|{{ISBNT|978-0-7434-9165-5}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Song of Experience''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''June 30, 2014''\n|{{ISBNT|978-0-7434-9166-2}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Fearful Symmetry''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=fearful}}\n|{{ISBNT|978-0-7434-9167-9}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Star Trek fictional works|List of ''Star Trek'' fictional works]]{{Snd}}Works writen from an in-unverse perspective, such as atlas, histories, and autobiographies.\n* ''[[TekWar#Novels|TekWar]]''{{Snd}}Science fiction novel series written by [[William Shatner]].\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist|30em}}\n\n=== Similarly named works ===\n{{Notelist-lr|30em}}\n\n=== Multiple authors ===\n{{Notelist-ua|30em}}\n\n=== As by other authors ===\n{{Notelist-lg|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|startrekbooks.com}}\n* {{URL|cygnus-x1.net/links/lcars/lcars2.php|Cygnus-X1's book guide}}\n* {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206005254/http://www.well.com:80/~sjroby/lcars/index.html|title=The Complete Starfleet Library|date=2015-02-06}}\n{{Memory Alpha|Novels|''Star Trek'' novels}}\n\n{{Star Trek publications}}\n{{Star Trek}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Star Trek novels}}\n[[Category:Book series introduced in 1967]]\n[[Category:Novels based on Star Trek| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of novels based on works|Star Trek]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||Star Trek comics and graphic novels published by Marvel Comics, DC Comics, IDW Publishing|Star Trek (comics)|original audio books, in-universe references, picture books, photo comics, and fictional biographies|List of Star Trek fictional works}}\n{{Short description|Novels based on Star Trek}}\n{{Italic title|string=Star Trek}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox book series\n| name = ''Star Trek''\n| image = Star Trek TOS logo.svg\n| author = ''Various''\n| country = [[United States]]\n| language = English\n| genre = [[Science fiction]]\n| publisher = {{Ubl\n  |[[Bantam Books]] (1967\u20131981)\n  |[[Random House]] (1974\u20132019)\n  |[[Simon & Schuster]] (1979\u2013present)\n  |[[Titan Books]] (2015\u2013present)\n  |Insight Editions (2016\u2013present)\n}}\n| pub_date = 1967\u2013present\n| number_of_books = 860 (estimate)\n| website = {{URL|startrekbooks.com}} (Simon & Schuster)\n}}\n'''''[[Star Trek]]''''' has a fifty-two year history of tie-in fiction, beginning with the 1967 publication of [[James Blish]]'s ''Star Trek 1''.{{Efn|Originally published as ''Star Trek''. Retitled ''Star Trek 1'' in 1975.}}<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Voyages of the Imagination: The Star Trek Fiction Companion|title-link=Voyages of Imagination|last=Ayers|first=Jeff|date=2006-11-14|publisher=[[Pocket Books]]|isbn=9781416503491|location=New York}}</ref> {{As of|2019|11}}, approximately 850 novels, [[short story]] [[anthologies]], novelizations, and omnibus editions, have been published.\n\nNovels based on ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]],'' ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation|The Next Generation]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Voyager|Voyager]]'', and ''[[Star Trek: Discovery|Discovery]]'', are in print. As recently as 2017, novels based on ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine|Deep Space Nine]]'' and ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise|Enterprise]]'' were published. Original concept series such as ''Prometheus'', ''[[Star Trek: New Frontier|New Frontier]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Titan|Titan]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Section 31|Section 31]]'', ''Seekers,'' and ''[[Star Trek: Vanguard|Vanguard]]'', have been published with some frequency since 1994.\n\nCurrent publishers of licensed [[tie-in]] and original fiction are [[Simon & Schuster]], via Gallery and Pocket Books imprints, [[Titan Books]], and souvenir book publisher Insight Editions. [[Bantam Books]] published licensed fiction from 1967 to 1981. Other publishers include: [[Western Publishing]], Random House imprints [[Ballantine Books|Ballantine]] and [[Del Rey Books]], [[Bookspan|Science Fiction Book Club]], and German publisher Cross Cult.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/1991/09/27/books-star-trek/|title=Books on ''Star Trek''|last=Svetkey|first=Benjamin|date=1991-09-27|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2010-03-03}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 20em;\"\n|+Key:\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |All novels published as paperback editions, except where indicated.\n|-\n|\u2020\n|{{Left|Hardcover first edition.}}\n|-\n|^\n|{{Left|Children's or young adult book.}}\n|-\n|\u25ca\n|{{Left|Published as an ebook exclusive.}}\n|-\n|\u2021\n|{{Left|Included in omnibus or anthology.}}\n|-\n|''{{Teal|Teal}}''\n|{{Left|Book line or flagship series name.}}\n|-\n|''{{NavyC|Navy}}''\n|{{Left|Miniseries name.}}\n|-\n|''{{Pink|Pink}}''\n|{{Left|Crossover series name.}}\n|-\n|ed.\n|{{Left|Omnibus or anthology editor(s).}}\n|-\n|et al.\n|{{Left|Multiple authors, see note.}}\n|}\n\n== Bantam Books (1967\u20131994) ==\n{{Anchor|Bantam Books}}{{Main|Star Trek (Bantam Books)}}\nBantam Books was the first licensed publisher of ''Star Trek'' tie-in fiction. All novels were published as [[mass market paperback]] editions. The popular reference ''[[Star Trek Lives!]]'' (1975), by [[Jacqueline Lichtenberg]], was also published by Bantam.\n\n=== Episode novelizations (1967\u20131994) ===\nAnthology collections of episode novelizations written by [[James Blish]] and [[J.A. Lawrence]]. ''Mudd's Angels'' (1978) includes the novelizations of \"[[Mudd's Women]]\" and \"[[I, Mudd]]\", and an original novella by Lawrence. ''The Day of the Dove'' (1985) is a variant of ''Star Trek 11'' (1975). ''Mudd's Enterprise'' (1994) is a variant of ''Mudd's Angels''.\n{{For|the photo comics adaptations of [[Star Trek: The Original Series|The Original Series]] episodes|List of Star Trek fictional works#Episode adaptations}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!Catalog{{\\}}ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek''\n| rowspan=\"12\" |James Blish\n|January 1967\n|F3459\n|-\n|''Star Trek 2''\n|February 1968\n|F3439\n|-\n|''Star Trek 3''\n|April 1969\n|F4371\n|-\n|''Star Trek 4''\n|July 1971\n|S7009\n|-\n|''Star Trek 5''\n|February 1972\n|S7300\n|-\n|''Star Trek 6''\n|April 1972\n|S7364\n|-\n|''Star Trek 7''\n|July 1972\n|S7480\n|-\n|''Star Trek 8''\n|November 1972\n|SP7550\n|-\n|''Star Trek 9''\n|August 1973\n|SP7808\n|-\n|''Star Trek 10''\n|February 1974\n|SP8401\n|-\n|''Star Trek 11''\n|April 1975\n|Q8717\n|-\n|''Star Trek 1''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|''Star Trek 1'' (1975) is a variant of ''Star Trek'' (1967), by James Blish.}} (variant)\n|May 1975\n|Q2114\n|-\n|''Star Trek 12''\n|James Blish and J.A. Lawrence\n|November 1977\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-11382-8}}\n|-\n|''Mudd's Angels''\n|J.A. Lawrence\n|May 1978\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-11802-1}}\n|-\n|''The Day of the Dove''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|''The Day of the Dove'' (1985) is a variant of ''Star Trek 11'' (1975), by James Blish.}} (variant)\n|James Blish\n|October 1985\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-25169-4}}\n|-\n|''Mudd's Enterprise''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|''Mudd's Enterprise'' (1994) is a variant of ''Mudd's Angels'' (1978), by J.A. Lawrence.}} (variant)\n|J.A. Lawrence\n|November 1994\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-56982-1}}\n|}\n=== Original novels (1970\u20131981) ===\nSeries of original novels is based on the [[Star Trek: The Original Series|television series of the same name]],{{Efn|No tie-in novels published by [[Bantam Books]] included the ''Original Series'' subtitle.}} not to be confused with the novelization series by James Blish. The series is cataloged as '''''Star Trek Adventures''''' by book discovery sites, such as [[Goodreads]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/series/106746-star-trek-adventures|title=Star Trek Adventures Series (16 books)|website=[[Goodreads]]|access-date=2017-12-15}}</ref> Bantam never applied a series name to the novels, instead marketing each entry as a \"new ''Star Trek'' adventure\". The novels are not numbered.\n{{Further|#Star Trek Adventures}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!Catalog{{\\}}ISBN\n|-\n|''[[Spock Must Die!]]''\n|James Blish\n|February 1970\n|H5515\n|-\n|''[[Spock, Messiah!]]''\n|Theodore Cogswell and Charles A. Spano, Jr.\n|September 1976\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-10159-5}}\n|-\n|''[[The Price of the Phoenix]]''\n|Sondra Marshak and Myrna Culbreath\n|July 1977\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-10978-2}}\n|-\n|''[[Planet of Judgment]]''\n|Joe Haldeman\n|August 1977\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-11145-0}}\n|-\n|''[[Vulcan!]]''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|Similarly named works:{{Blist|''Vulcan!'' (1978), novel by Kathleen Sky.|''Vulcan'' (2017) (''{{Teal|Hidden Universe Travel Guides}}''{{--)}}, fictional reference by Dayton Ward.}}|name=vulcan}}\n|Kathleen Sky\n|September 1978\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-12137-5}}\n|-\n|''[[The Starless World]]''\n|Gordon Eklund\n|November 1978\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-12371-8}}\n|-\n|''[[Trek to Madworld]]''\n|Stephen Goldin\n|January 1979\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-12618-0}}\n|-\n|''[[World Without End (Haldeman novel)|World Without End]]''\n|Joe Haldeman\n|February 1979\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-12583-4}}\n|-\n|''[[The Fate of the Phoenix]]''\n|Sondra Marshak and Myrna Culbreath\n|May 1979\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-12779-9}}\n|-\n|''Devil World''\n|Gordon Eklund\n|November 1979\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-13297-0}}\n|-\n|''Perry's Planet''\n|Jack C. Haldeman, II.\n|February 1980\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-13580-5}}\n|-\n|''The Galactic Whirlpool''\n|David Gerrold\n|October 1980\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-14242-9}}\n|-\n|''Death's Angel''\n|Kathleen Sky\n|April 1981\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-14703-X}}\n|}\n\n=== ''New Voyages'' (1976\u20131978) ===\n'''''Star Trek: The New Voyages''''' is a short story anthology series collecting [[fan fiction]] curated and edited by [[Sondra Marshak]] and [[Myrna Culbreath]]. Additional volumes were announced, but none were published.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|title=The Fate of the Phoenix|title-link=The Fate of the Phoenix|last=Marshak|first=Sondra|last2=Culbreath|first2=Myrna|date=May 1979|publisher=[[Bantam Books]]|isbn=9780553246384|series=Star Trek|location=New York|chapter=About the Authors|author-link=Sondra Marshak|author-link2=Myrna Culbreath}}</ref> Pocket Books's ''Strange New Worlds'' (1998\u20132016) series, edited by [[Dean Wesley Smith]], has a similar premise.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Editor(s)\n!Date\n!Catalog{{\\}}ISBN\n|-\n|''The New Voyages''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Sondra Marshak and Myrna Culbreath\n|March 1976\n|X2719\n|-\n|''The New Voyages 2''\n|January 1978\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-11392-5}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Classic Episodes'' (1991) ===\nIn 1991, Bantam collected the episode novelizations as a three volume omnibus edition. New material by [[D. C. Fontana]], [[Norman Spinrad]], and others, was included, however the novelizations of \"[[Mudd's Women]]\" and \"[[I, Mudd]]\" were excluded.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Classic Episodes 1''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|Includes all [[List of Star Trek: The Original Series episodes#Season 1 (1966\u201367)|''Star Trek'', Season 1]] episodes, except \"[[Mudd's Women]]\".}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |James Blish and J. A. Lawrence\n| rowspan=\"3\" |August 1991\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-29138-6}}\n|-\n|''The Classic Episodes 2''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|Includes all [[List of Star Trek: The Original Series episodes#Season 2 (1967\u201368)|''Star Trek'', Season 2]] episodes, except \"[[I, Mudd]]\".}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-29139-4}}\n|-\n|''The Classic Episodes 3''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|Includes all [[List of Star Trek: The Original Series episodes#Season 3 (1968\u201369)|''Star Trek'', Season 3]] episodes.}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-553-29140-8}}\n|}\n\n== Random House (1974\u20132019) ==\n{{Anchor|Ballantine Books|Random House|Del Rey Books|Del Rey}}\n[[Random House]] imprints [[Ballantine Books]], [[Del Rey Books]], and Random House Merchandising have published ''Star Trek'' tie-ins and novels.\n\n=== ''Star Trek Log'' (1974\u20131996) ===\n{{Anchor|Star Trek Log|Star Trek Logs}}{{Main|Star Trek Log (book series)}}\n'''''Star Trek Log'''''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|No books published by [[Ballantine Books]] included the ''Animated Series'' subtitle.}} is a series of novelizations based on episodes of ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series|The Animated Series]]''. Written by [[Alan Dean Foster]]. Published by Ballantine Books.\n\nEach volume includes new material linking the novelizations together.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.well.com/~sjroby/lcars/1974.html|title=Complete Starfleet Library - 1974 Star Trek Books|last=Roby|first=Steve|website=www.well.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116230143/http://www.well.com/~sjroby/lcars/1974.html|archive-date=January 16, 2015|access-date=2019-01-01|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Log One'' through ''Log Six'' adapted three episodes each, while ''Log Seven'' through ''Log Ten'' adapted one episode each. [[Del Rey Books]] reprinted the novelizations, with new cover designs, from 1984 to 1992.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pe.cgi?7900|title=Series: Star Trek Log|website=[[ISFDB]]|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log One''\n| rowspan=\"10\" |Alan Dean Foster\n|June 1974\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24014-6}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Two''\n|September 1974\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24184-3}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Three''\n|January 1975\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24260-2}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Four''\n|May 1975\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24435-4}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Five''\n|July 1975\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24532-6}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Six''\n|May 1976\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24655-1}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Seven''\n|June 1976\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-24965-8}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Eight''\n|August 1976\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-25141-5}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Nine''\n|February 1977\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-25557-7}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Ten''\n|January 1978\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-27212-9}}\n|}\n\n==== Omnibus editions (1993) ====\nOmnibus editions of Foster's novelizations available exclusively to comic book stores and newsstands.<ref name=\":6\" /> Published by Del Rey Books. ''Log Ten'' (1978) was excluded due to length. [[Pocket Books]] published similar editions, which included all ten volumes, for the United Kingdom market, the same year.\n{{Further|#Star Trek Log (reprint)}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log One{{\\}}Log Two{{\\}}Log Three''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Alan Dean Foster\n|January 1993\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-38247-1}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Four{{\\}}Log Five{{\\}}Log Six''\n|July 1993\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-38522-5}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Log Seven{{\\}}Log Eight{{\\}}Log Nine''\n|August 1993\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-38561-6}}\n|}\n\n==== 30th Anniversary editions (1996) ====\nOmnibus editions published as part of ''Star Trek''{{'s}} 30th Anniversary celebration. A serialized essay by Foster was included, as well as corrections to the original text. Published by Del Rey Books.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek: Log One & Two''\n| rowspan=\"5\" |Alan Dean Foster\n| rowspan=\"5\" |September 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-40939-6}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek: Log Three & Four''\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-40940-X}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek: Log Five & Six''\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-40941-8}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek: Log Seven & Eight''\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-40942-6}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek: Log Nine & Ten''\n|{{ISBNT|0-345-40943-4}}\n|}\n\n=== Gibraltar Library Binding (1977) ===\nIllustrated middle-grade novels published exclusively for libraries. Additional novels were announced in 1979, but were withdrawn for unknown reasons.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title \u2020^\n!Author(s)\n!Illustrator\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Truth Machine''\n|Sharon Lerner and Christopher Cerf\n|Jane Clark\n|January 1977\n|{{ISBNT|0-394-83575-1}}\n|-\n|''The Prisoner of Vega''\n|Sharon Lerner\n|Robert Swanson\n|October 1977\n|{{ISBNT|0-394-83576-X}}\n|}\n\n== Simon & Schuster (1979\u2013present) ==\n{{Anchor|Pocket Books|Gallery Books|Simon & Schuster}}\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"width: 20em;\"\n|+Notes:\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n* Novels are organized according to book line, series and miniseries, and crossover series, etc.\n* All novels are sorted by release date.\n*'''Many novels are listed more than once'''.\n|}\nSimon & Schuster imprint [[Pocket Books]] published ''Star Trek'' tie-ins from 1979 to 2016. [[Gallery Publishing Group|Gallery Books]] imprint has published a majority of releases since 2016.\n\nOther Simon & Schuster imprints known to have published ''Star Trek'' tie-ins include: Archway, Aladdin, Paula Wiseman, Wanderer, Minstrel, Byron Preiss, Wallaby, Weekly Reader, Pocket Star, Viz, Simon Spotlight, Simon & Schuster Interactive, and Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers. Imprints vary by book line, series, miniseries, printing, and market (e.g. country or language area).\n\n=== ''Star Trek'' (1979\u2013present) ===\n'''''Star Trek''''' book line is based on the [[Star Trek: The Original Series|television series of the same name]]. Paperback releases were numbered from 1979 to 2002. Hardback releases were not numbered. From 1987 to 1996, [[Titan Publishing Group|Titan Books]] reprinted original novels for the United Kingdom market using a different numbering scheme. Novels published since 2013 have included the ''Original Series'' subtitle. From 1979 until 2012, the subtitle rarely appeared on book covers.\n\n==== Film novelizations (1979\u20131992) ====\n{{For|photo comics adaptations of films|List of Star Trek fictional works#Film adaptations}}\nBased on the ''Star Trek'' [[List of Star Trek films and television series#The Original Series films|film series]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek: The Motion Picture''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 1)}}\n|Gene Roddenberry\n|December 1979\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-83088-0}}\n|-\n|''The Wrath of Khan'' \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 7)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Vonda N. McIntyre\n|July 1982\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-45610-5}}\n|-\n|''The Search for Spock''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|Similarly named works:{{Blist|''The Search for Spock'' (''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 17) (1984), novelization by Vonda N. McIntyre.|''Search for Spock'' (2017), puzzle book by Robb Pearlman.}}|name=search}} \u2021{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 17)}}\n|June 1984\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-49500-3}}\n|-\n|''The Voyage Home''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|Similarly named works:{{Blist|''The Voyage Home'' (1986), novelization by Vonda N. McIntyre.|''The Voyage Home'' (1986), young adult novelization by Peter Lerangis.}}|name=voyage}} \u2021\n| rowspan=\"2\" |December 1986\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-63266-3}}\n|-\n|''The Voyage Home''\u200a{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=voyage}} \u2020 (young adult)\n|Peter Lerangis\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-63243-4}}\n|-\n|''The Final Frontier''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|Similarly named works:{{Blist|''Final Frontier'' (1988), novel by [[Diane Carey]].|''The Final Frontier'' (1989), novelization by [[J.M. Dillard]].}}|name=final}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |J.M. Dillard\n|June 1989\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-68008-0}}\n|-\n|''The Undiscovered Country''\n|January 1992\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-75883-7}}\n|}\n\n==== Numbered novels (1979\u20132002) ====\nNumbered paperback releases:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Star Trek: The Motion Picture'' (novelization)\n|Gene Roddenberry\n|December 1979\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-83088-0}}\n|-\n|2\n|''[[The Entropy Effect]]''\n|Vonda N. McIntyre\n|June 1981\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-83692-7}}\n|-\n|3\n|''The Klingon Gambit''\n|Robert E. Vardeman\n|October 1981\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-83276-X}}\n|-\n|4\n|''The Covenant of the Crown''\n|Howard Weinstein\n|December 1981\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-83307-3}}\n|-\n|5\n|''The Prometheus Design''\n|Sondra Marshak and Myrna Culbreath\n|March 1982\n|{{ISBNT|0-6