es explores the lives of the {{USS|Enterprise|NCC-1701-E|2}} crew as [[Starfleet Academy]] cadets. A more recent series, ''Starfleet Academy'' (2010\u20132012), is based on the ''Kelvin'' Timeline films. ''Starfleet Academy'' (1997), a video game novelization by Diane Carey, is unrelated.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title ^\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Crisis on Vulcan''\n|Brad Strickland and Barbara Strickland\n|August 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00078-0}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Aftershock''\n|John Vornholt\n|September 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00079-9}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Cadet Kirk''\n|Diane Carey\n|October 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00077-2}}\n|}\n\n==== ''My Brother's Keeper'' (1999) ====\n'''''Star Trek: My Brother's Keeper''''' miniseries explores the friendship between [[Gary Mitchell (Star Trek)|Gary Mitchell]] and [[James T. Kirk]] prior to the episode \"[[Where No Man Has Gone Before]]\". Written by [[Michael Jan Friedman]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Republic''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 85)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Michael Jan Friedman\n| rowspan=\"3\" |January 1999\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01914-7}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Constitution''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 86)}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01919-8}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Enterprise''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=enterprise}}{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 87)}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01920-1}}\n|}\n\n==== ''New Earth'' (2000) ====\n{{Main|Star Trek: New Earth}}\n'''''Star Trek: New Earth''''' miniseries explores the period between ''[[Star Trek: The Motion Picture]]'' (1979) and ''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan|The Wrath of Khan]]'' (1982). ''Chainmail'' (2001), by Diane Carey, is a sequel to ''New Earth''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Wagon Train to the Stars''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 89)}}\n|Diane Carey\n| rowspan=\"2\" |June 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04296-3}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Belle Terre''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 90)}}\n|Dean Wesley Smith and Diane Carey\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04297-1}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Rough Trails''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 91)}}\n|L.A. Graf\n| rowspan=\"2\" |July 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-03600-9}}\n|-\n|4\n|''The Flaming Arrow''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 92)}}\n|Kathy Oltion and Jerry Oltion\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-78562-1}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Thin Air''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 93)}}\n|Kristine Kathryn Rusch and Dean Wesley Smith\n| rowspan=\"2\" |August 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-78577-X}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Challenger''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{Teal|Star Trek}}'', Book 94)}}\n|Diane Carey\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04298-X}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Eugenics Wars'' (2001\u20132005) ====\n'''''Star Trek: The Eugenics Wars''''' miniseries explores the life of [[Khan Noonien Singh]] from his rise to power in South Asia until his abandonment on [[Ceti Alpha V]] by the ''Enterprise''. The series was developed by [[Greg Cox (writer)|Greg Cox]] and [[John J. Ordover]].<ref name=\":0\" />{{Rp|133}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title \u2020\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Rise and Fall of Khan Noonien Singh'', {{Abbr|Vol.|Volume}} 1\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Greg Cox\n|June 26, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02127-3}}\n|-\n|''The Rise and Fall of Khan Noonien Singh'', Vol. 2\n|April 23, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-0643-5}}\n|-\n|''To Reign in Hell: The Exile of Khan Noonien Singh''\n|January 4, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-5711-0}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Janus Gate'' (2002) ====\n'''''Star Trek: The Janus Gate''''' miniseries follows the events of \"[[The Naked Time]]\". Written by [[L.A. Graf]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Present Tense''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |L.A. Graf\n| rowspan=\"2\" |May 21, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-03635-1}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Future Imperfect''\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-03636-X}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Past Prologue''\n|June 25, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4596-1}}\n|}\n