 (1995) ===\n{{Anchor|Star Trek Log (reprint)}}{{Main|Star Trek Log (book series)}}\n'''''Star Trek Log''''' reprints of the novelizations based on ''[[Star Trek: The Animated Series|The Animated Series]]'' originally published by [[Ballantine Books]] from 1974 to 1978. Published by Pocket Books specifically for the United Kingdom and Australian markets.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pe.cgi?7900|title=Series: Star Trek Log|website=[[ISFDB]]|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Released\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek Logs 1{{Snd}}3''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Alan Dean Foster\n|April 1995\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-85403-8}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Logs 4{{Snd}}6''\n|May 1995\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-85404-6}}\n|-\n|''Star Trek Logs 7{{Snd}}10''\n|June 1995\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-85405-4}}\n|}\n\n=== Shatner and Reeves-Stevens series (1995\u20132007) ===\n{{Anchor|Shatner concept series|The Shatnerverse|Shatnerverse}}\nCreated by [[William Shatner]], and co-written by [[Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens]]. The series explores events following [[James T. Kirk|James Kirk]]'s resurrection after his apparent death at the end of ''[[Star Trek Generations|Generations]]'' (1994). Characters from the films and various television series appear in the novels. However, the continuity within the Shatner and Reeves-Stevens series is independent of all other book lines.\n\nThe novels have been marketed \"as by William Shatner\" by Simon & Schuster, and have not been given an official name. The colloquial name, \"The Shatnerverse\", was used by [[Memory Alpha]] and [[ISFDb]] in the recent past to differentiate the series from other book lines. Fans have organized the series into three trilogies: \"Odyssey\", named after the omnibus edition of the first trilogy of novels, followed by \"Mirror Universe\", and \"Totality\".\n\n''Academy'' (2007), a flagship series created by the Reeves-Stevenses, contains links to ''The Ashes of Eden'' (1995).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title \u2020\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''[[The Ashes of Eden]]'' \u2021\n| rowspan=\"7\" |William Shatner\n|June 1995\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-52035-0}}\n|-\n|''[[The Return (Shatner novel)|The Return]]'' \u2021\n|April 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-52610-3}}\n|-\n|''[[Avenger (Shatner novel)|Avenger]]'' \u2021\n|May 1997\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-55132-9}}\n|-\n|''Odyssey'' (omnibus)\n|September 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02547-3}}\n|-\n|''[[Spectre (novel)|Spectre]]''\n|May 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00878-1}}\n|-\n|''[[Dark Victory (novel)|Dark Victory]]''\n|April 1999\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00882-X}}\n|-\n|''[[Preserver (novel)|Preserver]]''\n|July 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02125-7}}\n|-\n|''[[Captain's Peril]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |William Shatner,{{Indent|2}}with Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens\n|October 8, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4819-7}}\n|-\n|''[[Captain's Blood]]''\n|December 9, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02129-X}}\n|-\n|''[[Captain's Glory]]''\n|August 22, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-5343-3}}\n|}\n\n=== Video game novelizations (1996\u201397) ===\nNovelizations of the ''Star Trek'' video games. ''Star Trek: Klingon'' (1996) was also dramatized as an audiobook. A novelization of ''Star Trek: Borg'' (1996) was announced, but was not published.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n{{Further|List of Star Trek fictional works#Interactive movie dramatizations}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Star Trek: Klingon''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|Novelization of ''Star Trek: Klingon'' (1996), an [[interactive movie]] game developed by Simon & Schuster Interactive.}}{{Efn-lr|Similarly named works:{{Blist|''Klingon'' (1996), audio dramatization by Hilary Bader.|''Klingon'' (1996), novelization by Dean Wesley Smith and Kristine Kathryn Rusch.}}}}\n|Dean Wesley Smith and Kristine Kathryn Rusch\n|May 1996\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-00257-0}}\n|-\n|''Starfleet Academy''{{Hsp}}{{Efn|Novelization of ''Star Trek: Starfleet Academy'' (1997), a three-dimensional simulation video game published by [[Interplay Entertainment]].}}\n|Diane Carey\n|June 1997\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01550-8}}\n|}\n\n=== ''New Frontier'' (1997\u20132015) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: New Frontier}}\n'''''Star Trek: New Frontier''''' was the first ''Star Trek'' book line not to be based on a television series. The novels follow the crew of the {{Ship|USS|Excalibur|NCC-26517|6|wl=no}}, under the command of [[Mackenzie Calhoun]]. Created by [[John J. Ordover]]. Written by [[Peter David]].\n\n==== Numbered novels (1997\u20132001) ====\nNumbered paperback and hardcover releases:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''House of Cards'' \u2021\n| rowspan=\"18\" |Peter David\n| rowspan=\"2\" |July 1997\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01395-5}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Into the Void'' \u2021\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01396-3}}\n|-\n|3\n|''The Two-Front War'' \u2021\n| rowspan=\"2\" |August 1997\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01397-1}}\n|-\n|4\n|''End Game''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=endgame}} \u2021\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-01398-X}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Martyr''\n|March 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02036-6}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Fire on High''\n|April 1998\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02037-4}}\n|-\n|7\n|''The Quiet Place''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |November 1999\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02079-X}}\n|-\n|8\n|''Dark Allies''\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-02080-3}}\n|-\n|9\n|''Requiem''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|Excalibur}}'', Book 1)}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |September 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04238-6}}\n|-\n|10\n|''Renaissance''{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|Excalibur}}'', Book 2)}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04239-4}}\n|-\n|11\n|''Restoration'' \u2020{{Indent|2}}{{Small|(''{{NavyC|Excalibur}}'', Book 3)}}\n|November 2000\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04243-2}}\n|-\n|12\n|''Being Human''\n|October 30, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-671-04240-8}}\n|-\n|13\n|''Gods Above''\n|September 30, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-1858-1}}\n|-\n|14\n|''Stone and Anvil'' \u2020\n|October 28, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2957-5}}\n|-\n|15\n|''After the Fall'' \u2020\n|November 30, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9184-X}}\n|-\n|16\n|''Missing in Action'' \u2020\n|February 28, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-1080-