e\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Broken Bow'' \u2020\n|Diane Carey\n|October 2, 2001\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4862-6}}\n|-\n|''Shockwave'' \u2020\n|Paul Ruditis\n|October 15, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6455-9}}\n|-\n|''The Expanse''\n|J.M. Dillard\n|September 30, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-8485-1}}\n|}\n\n==== Original novels (2002\u20132006) ====\nThe novels were more closely plotted to events of the television series, as compared to other book lines. ''Daedalus'' (2003) and ''Daedalus's Children'' (2004) form a two-part novel that explores the aftermath of a prototype warp ship's disastrous launch thirteen years prior the launch of the {{Ship|2=Enterprise|3=NX-01}}. Elements of the ''Daedalus'' duology are expanded upon in subsequent novels.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''By the Book''\n|Dean Wesley Smith and Kristine Kathryn Rusch\n|January 2, 2002{{Efn|The publication date of ''By the Book'' (''{{Teal|Enterprise}}''{{--)}} (2002), by [[Dean Wesley Smith]] and [[Kristine Kathryn Rusch]], is listed by [[Books In Print]] and [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] as {{Date|2001-01-02|MDY}}. The novel's verso lists the publication date as January 2002.}}\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4871-5}}\n|-\n|''What Price Honor?''\n|Dave Stern\n|October 29, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6278-5}}\n|-\n|''Surak's Soul''\n|J.M. Dillard\n|February 25, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6280-7}}\n|-\n|''Daedalus''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Dave Stern\n|November 25, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-7118-0}}\n|-\n|''Daedalus's Children''\n|April 27, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-7646-8}}\n|-\n|''Rosetta''\n|January 31, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0956-9}}\n|}\n\n==== Relaunch novels (2006\u20132008) ====\nInterlinked novels set after the episode \"[[These Are the Voyages...]]\":\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Last Full Measure''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Andy Mangels and Michael A. Martin\n|April 25, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0358-7}}\n|-\n|''The Good That Men Do''\n|February 27, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-0-7434-4001-1}}\n|-\n|''Kobayashi Maru''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=kobayashi}}\n|August 26, 2008\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-5480-6}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Romulan War'' (2009\u20132011) ====\n'''''Star Trek: Enterprise'''{{Snd}}'''Romulan War''''' explores the events of the [[Romulan|Earth\u2013Romulan War]] from the perspective of the ''Enterprise'' crew.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.startrek.com/article/michael-a-martin-on-the-romulan-war-and-more-part-1|title=Michael A. Martin On The Romulan War And More, Part 1|date=2011-10-25|website=Star Trek|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> Written by [[Michael A. Martin]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Beneath the Raptor's Wing''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Michael A. Martin\n|October 20, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-0798-0}}\n|-\n|''To Brave the Storm''\n|October 25, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0715-4}}\n|}\n\n==== ''Rise of the Federation'' (2013\u20132017) ====\n'''''Star Trek: Enterprise'''{{Snd}}'''Rise of the Federation''''' explores the creation of the [[United Federation of Planets]], and the eventual rise of [[Jonathan Archer]] to President of the Federation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://christopherlbennett.wordpress.com/2013/04/08/announcing-enterprise-rise-of-the-federation-book-2/|title=Announcing ENTERPRISE: RISE OF THE FEDERATION\u2026 Book 2!|last=Bennett|first=Christopher L.|authorlink=Christopher L. Bennett|date=2013-04-08|website=Christopher L. Bennett: Written Worlds|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> Written by [[Christopher L. Bennett]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''A Choice of Futures''\n| rowspan=\"5\" |Christopher L. Bennett\n|June 25, 2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-0674-0}}\n|-\n|''Tower of Babel''\n|March 25, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-4964-8}}\n|-\n|''Uncertain Logic''\n|March 24, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-7911-9}}\n|-\n|''Live by the Code''\n|March 29, 2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-7913-3}}\n|-\n|''Patterns of Interference''\n|August 29, 2017\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-6570-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Stargazer'' (2002\u20132004) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Stargazer}}\n'''''Star Trek: Stargazer''''' follows a young [[Jean-Luc Picard]] in command of the {{Ship|USS|Stargazer|wl=no}}. Written by [[Michael Jan Friedman]]. ''Reunion'' (1991) and ''The Valiant'' (2000), also by Friedman, are linked with the series.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Gauntlet''\n| rowspan=\"6\" |Michael Jan Friedman\n| rowspan=\"2\" |April 30, 2002\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2792-0}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Progenitor''\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-2794-7}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Three''\n|July 29, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4852-9}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Oblivion''\n|August 26, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4854-5}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Enigma''\n|July 27, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4856-1}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Maker''\n|August 31, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-4858-8}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Lost Era'' (2003\u20132014) ===\n{{Anchor|Star Trek: The Lost Era|The Lost Era|Lost Era}}{{Main|Star Trek: The Lost Era}}\n'''''Star Trek: The Lost Era''''' explores events prior to the ''Next Generation'' episode \"[[Encounter at Farpoint]]\". ''The Buried Age'' (2007), Christopher L. Bennett, and the ''Terok Nor'' (2008) series were marketed as \"Tales of the Lost Era\". The novels are not numbered.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''The Sundered''\n|Michael A. Martin and Andy Mangels\n|July 29, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6401-X}}\n|-\n|''Serpents Among the Ruins''\n|David R. George III\n|August 26, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6403-6}}\n|-\n|''The Art of the Impossible''\n|Keith DeCandido\n|September 30, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6405-2}}\n|-\n|''Well of Souls''\n|Ilsa J. Bick\n|October 28, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6375-7}}\n|-\n|''Deny Thy Father''\n|Jeff Mariotte\n|November 25, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6409-5}}\n|-\n|''Catalyst of Sorrows''\n|Margaret Wander Bonanno\n|December 30, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-6407-9}}\n|-\n|''One Constant Star''\n|David R. George III\n|May 27, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-5021-7}}\n|}\n\n=== I.K.S. ''Gorkon'' (2003\u20132005) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Klingon Empire}}\n'''''Star Trek:'' I.K.S. ''Gorkon''''' follows the exploits of a [[Klingon]] destroyer ordered into unexplored space to find new planets to conquer in the name of The Empire. Written by [[Keith DeCandido]]. Relaunched as '''''Klingon Empire''''' in 2008.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''A Good Day to Die''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Keith DeCandido\n|October 28, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-5714-5}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Honor Bound''{{Hsp}}{{Efn-lr|name=honor}}\n|November 25, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-5716-1}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Enemy Territory''\n|March 1, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0014-6}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Signature Edition'' (2003\u201304) ===\nThe '''''Signature Edition''''' omnibus series collects two or more related novels from the ''Star Trek'' and ''Next Generation'' book lines. The editions include amplifying material, such as author's notes, essays, and interviews.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Pantheon''\n|Michael Jan Friedman\n|September 16, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-8511-4}}\n|-\n|''The Q Continuum''\n|Greg Cox\n|October 7, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-8508-4}}\n|-\n|''Worlds in Collision''\n|Judith and Garfield Reeves-Stevens\n|November 4, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-8509-2}}\n|-\n|''Imzadi Forever''\n|Peter David\n|December 2, 2003\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-8510-6}}\n|-\n|''Duty, Honor, Redemption''\n|Vonda N. McIntyre\n|October 26, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9660-4}}\n|-\n|''The Hand of Kahless''\n|John M. Ford and Michael Jan Friedman\n|November 16, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9659-0}}\n|-\n|''Sand and Stars''\n|Diane Duane and A. C. Crispin\n|December 7, 2004\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9658-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Titan'' (2005\u20132017) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Titan}}\n'''''Star Trek: Titan''''' is flagship series set aboard the {{Ship|USS|Titan|wl=no}}, under the command of [[William Riker]]. The starship ''Titan'' was introduced in ''[[Star Trek: Nemesis|Nemesis]]'' (2002). Not all novels are numbered by Simon & Schuster.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Taking Wing''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Michael A. Martin and Andy Mangels\n|March 29, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9627-2}}\n|-\n|2\n|''The Red King''\n|September 27, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|0-7434-9628-0}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Orion's Hounds''\n|Christopher L. Bennett\n|December 27, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0950-X}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Sword of Damocles''\n|Geoffrey Thorne\n|November 27, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-2694-0}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Over a Torrent Sea''\n|Christopher L. Bennett\n|February 24, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-9497-0}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Synthesis''\n|James Swallow\n|October 27, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-0914-4}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{Unknown|}}\n|''Fallen Gods''\n|Michael A. Martin\n|July 31, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-6062-3}}\n|-\n|''Absent Enemies'' \u25ca\n|John Jackson Miller\n|February 24, 2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-6299-9}}\n|-\n|''Sight Unseen''\n|James Swallow\n|September 29, 2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4767-8316-1}}\n|-\n|''Fortune of War''\n|David Mack\n|November 28, 2017\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-5011-5200-9}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Vanguard'' (2005\u20132012) ===\n{{Main|Star Trek: Vanguard}}\n'''''Star Trek: Vanguard''''' is a flagship concept series concurrent with the events of ''Star Trek''. Set aboard {{Ship|Starbase 47|Vanguard|wl=no}} on the edge of an unexplored region of space known as the Taurus Reach. Conceived and written by Dayton Ward, Kevin Dilmore, and David Mack. The novella, ''Distant Early Warning'' (2006), by Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore, is a prequel to ''Vanguard''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|1\n|''Harbinger''\n|David Mack\n|July 26, 2005\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-0774-4}}\n|-\n|2\n|''Summon the Thunder''\n|Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|June 27, 2006\n|{{ISBNT|1-4165-2400-2}}\n|-\n|3\n|''Reap the Whirlwind''\n|David Mack\n|May 22, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-3414-3}}\n|-\n|4\n|''Open Secrets''\n|Dayton Ward\n|April 28, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-4792-1}}\n|-\n|5\n|''Precipice''\n|David Mack\n|November 24, 2009\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4391-3011-7}}\n|-\n|6\n|''Declassified''\n|Dayton Ward, et al.{{Efn-ua|''Declassified'' (''{{Teal|Vanguard}}'', Book 6) (2011) by Dayton Ward, Kevin Dilmore, Marco Palmieri, and David Mack.}}\n|June 28, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0691-1}}\n|-\n|7\n|''What Judgments Come''\n|Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore\n|September 27, 2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-0863-2}}\n|-\n|8\n|''Storming Heaven''\n|David Mack\n|March 27, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-5070-9}}\n|-\n|{{Unknown|}}\n|''In Tempest's Wake'' \u25ca\n|Dayton Ward\n|October 2, 2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4516-9589-2}}\n|}\n\n=== ''Mirror Universe'' (2007\u20132009) ===\n'''''Star Trek: Mirror Universe''''' explores the [[Mirror Universe]] introduced in ''Star Trek'' episode \"[[Mirror, Mirror (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Mirror, Mirror]]\". ''Glass Empires'' (2007) and ''Obsidian Alliances'' (2007) are collections of three novellas each. ''Shards and Shadows'' (2009) is a short story anthology. ''The Sorrows of Empire'' (2009) was expanded from a novella collected in ''Glass Empires''. ''Fearful Symmetry'' (2008) and ''The Soul Key'' (2009), by Olivia Wood, and ''Disavowed'' (2014), by David Mack, are linked to the series. Early solicitations of Wood's novels included the ''Mirror Universe'' logo, in addition to the ''Deep Space Nine'' marquee.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Author(s)\n!Date\n!ISBN\n|-\n|''Glass Empires''\n|Michael Sussman, et al.{{Efn-ua|''Glass Empires'' (''{{Teal|Mirror Universe}}''{{--)}} (2007) by Michael Sussman, with Dayton Ward and Kevin Dilmore, David Mack, and Greg Cox.}}\n|February 20, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-2459-5}}\n|-\n|''Obsidian Alliances''\n|Keith DeCandido, Peter David, and Sara Shaw{{Efn-lg|Sara Shaw is pseudonymous with [[David Alan Mack|David Mack]].}}\n|March 20, 2007\n|{{ISBNT|978-1-4165-2471-7}}\n|-\n|''Shards and Shadows'' (anthology)\n|Marco Palmieri and Margaret Clark, 